animal.description:
If you have ANY QUESTIONS or are truly interested in adopting any animal from PAW Animal Shelter Please, fillout an adoption application FIRST! WE are a high intake No Kill Shelter ran by a staff of 4 and do not always have time to answer every question asked by so many. If you are a good fit for the animal you are interested in -we will call to speak with you, If we feel you are not a good fit , we will contact you about other pets that may be a good fit for your home. Many people are losing the opportunity to adopt the animal they want because they fail to put in an application and the pet was adopted before we could answer your email. .If you have applied for an animal in our facility and have not received a response within 7 days, PLEASE call or contact us again. Though we do our best in trying to answer all emails in a timely manner, sometimes things get away from us, get lost or misplaced. It is never our intention to ignore a request about an adoptable animal in our facility.

Sandy Brown, Director, PAW Animal Shelter

animal.description:
1217053

I need a single family home since I seem to be part pittie! I can NOT go to a home in a city or county with pitbull restrictions!

Sabin is the sweetest 3 yr old lab mix pup he loves to be with humans so much! He does amazing outside the crate when left alone, I usually just leave him in my room. At 70 lbs, Sabin still thinks he is a lap dog and loves cuddling and staring into his humans eyes! 

Sabin gets along with dogs that are bigger than 30 lbs and are on the submissive side. Slow intro is always advised. He loves my twos dogs and really loves to play. No small dogs or cats though. Sabin does really well on a leash walking with the dogs he already knows, but he can have leash reactivity when meeting new dogs, so he needs a human who will keep working on the training with him. He is very food motivated and I have had success training him by bribing with treats! 

He is allergic to many foods and is on a special kibble diet (Instinct turkey brand) that will need to be followed. He had an ACL surgery (over 2 months ago) and is nicely recovering at home we are now going on short walks! Sabin will truly make a wonderful dog for anyone who is lucky enough to adopt him

animal.description: Meet Drax! While he is as burly as his namesake, all Drax wants is a cuddle buddy who will give him all the belly rubs. Drax is about 4 years old and about 52 pounds, and has the cutest speckled coat ever. He loves to play with toys, especially those with squeakies, and will even jump in the air to catch them-because nothing goes over his head. Drax does well in his crate and is quickly mastering skills like sit in his foster home, but still needs some work on the leash. He can be a chill lap dog, but also loves to run and fetch. Drax gets along fine with the other dogs in his foster home, but would also be fine with being an only dog so all the toys and attention can be his. He would do best in a house with no cats though. Sometimes Drax doesn't know how big he is, so may not be the best fit for a house with young children, but if everyone is over about 10, bring them on! Are you his forever cuddle partner? Contact us now! All Dallas Pets Alive adoptable pets are spayed or neutered, microchipped, and up to date on vaccines upon adoption. The standard minimum donation for dogs over six months to seven years is $200, puppies under six months is $250, dogs eight years and over are $100 unless specified otherwise. You can view all the adoptable pets and fill out an adoption application online on our website at http://dallaspetsalive.org/adopt/adoptable-dogs/ . For more information, you can email adopt@dallaspetsalive.org.

animal.description:
Meet Peggy
She is one of our sweet seniors, approximately 9 years old. She was abandoned in a hotel room with 2 of her friends. All 3 dogs were in fairly rough condition, and Peggy was no exception.
Peggy had a large hernia, a wire from a fractured jaw that should have been removed ages ago, rotten teeth, and an abscess on her face. She got all fixed up, and now she’s ready for a new home.

In true chihuahua form, she has a bit of a tude. If you aren’t a fan of chihuahuas, Peggy is not for you. She is skeptical of people at first and can be a little snippy (although she doesn’t have many teeth left so not much damage done there) but once she loves you, she is as loyal as can be.

Her favorite things are car rides, smooches on her cheek, and sleeping under the covers with her favorite human.

An ideal home for Peggy would have dogs her size only, a human she can snuggle, and no small children or kitties.

If you’re interested in Peggy, please submit an application to www.radrescueinc.org

animal.description:
Meet ROCK! Rock is a sweet 4 year old adult, 40 pound, tan mix. Don't let the stern look fool you, Rock is adorable, happy, outgoing and loves to snuggle/get attention from his humans! While he settles down nicely to hang our with the family, he also loves to go for walks, especially if he gets to meet new people. 

Rock found himself through no fault of his own in a rural North Carolina shelter. Poor Rock did not understand why no one came to get him and he had lost the comforts of a home. PetConnect came to his rescue and has brought him to the DC area to find his new home that will adore him furever. 

If you are looking for a very sweet, happy dog who will greet you with wiggle butts and gentle "kisses", Rock may be the one for you. He adores people of all ages, particularly loves to cuddle, get pets, and will make a wonderful family pet that is happy to join in the activities. He seems to understand housetraining and appropriate chew items. He would be a great companion to curl up in your lap to hang out on a cool winter evening. Rock is neutered, up-to-date on vaccines and preventatives and eager to find a family to love! The adoption fee for Rock is $350, which includes routine vetting, vaccines, spay/neuter, and heartworm treatment. 

***Please note that the first step in the adoption process is to complete an application so that we can discuss which dogs are best fits for you and for them. An important step in the process is to complete a vet check. Vetting of current and past pets is very important to us, thus we will be speaking with the vet(s) listed on your application to ensure that your current and previous pet(s) are kept up to date on vaccines (including rabies ) , spayed or neutered, maintained on appropriate monthly preventatives and examined annually by your vet.*** Complete an online application, and contact Robin at kinstondogs@verizon.net if you would like more information on Rock!.

animal.description:
Meet Tink!

This GORGEOUS little pocket pittie is Tinker Bell! She is tiny but mighty, has lots of hops, loves snuggles, and will sit or lay down for treats. This girl will do pretty much anything for a snacky snack!

She came to us from Maricopa County Animal Care after one of our volunteers saw her at the shelter. She wasn't loving shelter life so we busted her outta there in hopes of finding her a forever home!

Tink is quickly becoming a volunteer favorite and attends our weekly Mutt Manners training classes! This girl loves to learn!

She is approximately 2 years old, spayed, vaccinated and microchipped. Her ideal home would be one without other pets because she wants to keep her people all to herself and be your one and only. 

If you're interested in meeting her, please submit an adoption application: https://www.oneloveaz.org/adoption-process

All dogs in our VIP (Very Important Pits) Program receive post adoption support and access to our free weekly Mutt Manners training classes. 

Adoption Fees vary based on shelter promotions but are generally less than $50.

If you are interested in making an adoption appointment to meet Desiree, please email matt.pricelesspets@gmail.com

Desiree is a chocolate lab mix from Tijuana. She came from the streets and has the battle scars to prove it. Desiree is a nervous girl and will need someone who has the time and patience to show her that the world is safe. Desiree can be very fearful with strangers and will nip if she feels overwhelmed. For this reason, she is only handled by our most experienced and dog savvy volunteers. 

Desiree would do best in a home with an experienced and patient dog owner. She does well with other dogs but she is not good with children. 

**Please note: Desiree does have a bite on her record. She bit a volunteer as she was being loaded into a crate on her way to the veterinarian. We would recommend a home without children due to her history. She does not do well going into or out of crates. Desiree will also attempt to bite if she feels threatened and cannot escape.**

We are just getting to know Desiree and we will provide updates as we learn more about her.

animal.description: Shelby has a bit of a sad story to tell... her mom passed away and her and her little brother, Bear, were left alone in the home for a while until an organization was contacted to help them find homes or rescue. We are so glad that the Helping Paw Project reached out to us to help Shelby. Thanks to amazing volunteers we were able to commit to her. We had a foster step up for Shelby and a driver willing to take her to meet her new foster mom today. Shelby is a pretty chill girl and seems to be fully housebroken. She gets along great with other dogs and formerly lived in a home with a cat for a little while and has been good with children. She is very sweet and gentle and we believe would fit in and just about any home. Shelby is up to date on all of her vetting but we will be taking her in to get all checked over as she has had some trouble with ear infections in the past and we want to make sure that her ears are looking and feeling OK now.Shelby will be available for adoption in a couple of weeks after we get to know her better. She will also be available as a 'forever foster/sponsor me' girl if a family would like to offer that for her.

animal.description:
Ruby is a smart, confident dog who is ready for her forever home. She’s about 1.5 to 2 years old and is an absolute love bug. She will go in her crate after a couple of barks to let you know that she’s doing it under duress but then she quickly calms down and naps. Ruby loves to play and snuggle. She knows “sit” and “off” and “down” but will need some work on leash manners as she just wants to go everywhere as soon as she can get there. She loves treats and is quite playful - she probably would do better with another dog or an active owner who is going to take her for lots of exercise and safe dog parks. She seems to love everyone and every animal she comes across. She is really curious about cats but so far, I have not found a cat that was too keen on meeting her. I have a feeling she may be a bit exuberant for most cats. Ruby just wants to sit at your feet and be close by for all your adventures. She is game for just about anything - she likes walks, she likes car rides and will hop right in car and then jump on the seat and she likes just hanging out at home chewing on bones, toys or pig ears. She is not destructive and would be a great addition to any active family.

Email info@habitat4paws.org for an application.

**Because we require home visits, we only adopt locally to the Dallas/Fort Worth area. For more on adoption policies, please see the Adopt page of our website, www.habitat4paws.org.

animal.description:
Ella was rescued by a Good Samaritan that reached out to our rescue. Pictures do not do this girl justice. She is big & beautiful. Her foster Dad says she has been the perfect house guest-house trained, not demanding or high maintenance. She adores her foster Dad & is very much a velcro dog. We believe Ella is an Anatolian Shepherd mix. She matches the temperament description: Bold, Intelligent, Steady, Independent, Confident, Proud and yes...stubborn. Ella has met a few dogs, small & medium, and seems indifferent to their presence. Due to her breed, an experienced adopter is preferred. The perfect match would be a home with a patient family. This girl will need time to adjust to new situations and family. Older children only due to age & size. Everyone that meets her, falls in love.


If you are interested in one of our animals, please complete an application. The application link can be found on our Petfinder homepage under the picture. You may also find our application on our website at www.teammemphis.org  under the Our Rescue page. If they are listed on our website, their adoptions have not been finalized yet. That does not mean that we have not received several applications, already. Please complete an application if you are interested and we will keep you apprised of their current status. We are all volunteers who work full-time jobs and have animals of our own, so please be patient with us. We will get back with you as quickly as possible.

animal.description:
Sweet Sienna is the easy going gal you’ve been looking for. This 4 year old, 50lbs gal hails from the stray streets of Chicago. Her past traumas may be unknown but she is as loving as can be. Sienna has some ocular damage that is likely permanent and left her with limited vision in her left eye. Have no worries, as it has no impact and doesn’t cause any pain. Sienna is potty trained and crate trained. She is learning commands-- now knows sit, and walks well on a leash. She also comes when you call her. This gentle girl likes people, but prefers no kids as they make her a little nervous. Sienna has a little "Stranger-danger" at first and is a go slow kinda gal. Sienna is an introvert and likes a quiet slow pace. She’s also dog friendly. However, she is not the romp and wrestle type. She prefers no contact sports like chase. Sienna loves to cuddle and enjoys dressing up. Just when you think it can’t get better, it does!! She loves to sleep in your bed or on her own cozy dog bed all night long. She can also be trusted out when her humans are away. Sienna is a gentle, calm girl looking for a quiet home to share her life with.


Our adoption fee is $260 for dogs over 5 months of age and includes all vaccinations, spay/neuter, micro chip implantation and registration/transfer, heartworm test and much more. Puppies up to 5 months of age are $275 and this includes all sets of puppy vaccinations, spay/neuter, microchip implantation and registration and more. To adopt, go to www.fosterpetoutreach.org to complete an application.
Please note: Foster Pet Outreach tries to limit our adoptions to an area within approximately 60 miles of Peoria, Illinois.

animal.description:
OUR ADOPTION PROCESS AND APPLICATION IS AVAILABLE AT WWW.SOHODOGRESCUE.ORG AND OUR ADOPTION FEE IS $275

Nash is a very handsome, young purebred Border Collie who is ready for his forever home.  He is just under a year old, a great weight at 38 pounds, and he has a gorgeous black tri coat and full tail.  Nash is housebroken, crate-trained, knows some basic obedience commands and he rides nicely in the car when he is not trying to “chase” the cars driving in the opposite direction!  Nash does need work walking on the leash.  He will try to chase cars, race to greet other dogs or chase the random cat or squirrel, and you have to be ready for his pull in that direction.
Nash loves people.  He is a medium Velcro dog who wants to be with you but does not have to be underfoot – hanging out in the same room, watching TV or getting belly scratches, is fine with him!  Nash has not had a lot of opportunities to meet other dogs, and while he really enjoys playing with other dogs he is still learning how to properly greet them – crazy excited yelping is not the answer!  Nash is a medium-to-high energy dog with an “off switch”, who loves to walk, hike, explore, play ball, play tug-of-war, play with toys and play chase, and then nap.  
The ideal home for Nash is active and fun, with plenty of time for this friendly, energetic young guy. A fenced yard and another happy young dog are important, children over the age of 12 are fine, but cats would not appreciate meeting Nash in their home!  It is also important that his family continue his training – he has so much potential and we know that he is and will be an amazing dog.  If you can see Nash in your home, as part of your family, apply today!  Nash is fostered in Clarksville, TN.

animal.description:
My name is Paprika.  I am about 4 years old but very puppyish and goofy - I'm sure to make you smile and laugh with my sunny personality.
I have been on a few adventures in my life.  When rescued by DRNM in mid 2019, I was pregnant with 9 puppies. My puppies and I found homes; when I was spayed, precautions were taken since I have Von Willebrand and came through surgery with flying colors.  Over time I have been able to withstand normal little nicks, cuts and scratches that are part of a doggie life and heal just fine.

However, this has never kept me from being a bouncy ball of fun, I am a puppy trapped in a giant body!  My favorite things in the world are food, cuddling, doggie toys and humans and I will do anything for those.

I  am super affectionate and I LOVE PEOPLE, I will lick you to death, follow you everywhere and I am very good at coming when you call me because being with you is my greatest joy in life. 

I am always alert and eager to please. I pay attention to details, I always want to make sure that your house is safe and to be told that I am a good girl taking care of my peeps. I am not a barker at all, but I will definitely let you know if any cats, squirrels or delivery men are near.

I know all my basic commands and I will follow any of them immediately if food is a reward (I was a starved street dog at some point and food is a BIGGIE for me). However, I need an firm owner because when there is no food treat involved to make me sit pretty, I do behave a like a giant, fun-loving puppy. I need to be reminded of what the rules are that you want me to follow. I forget that I have this big, strong body, so I do need rules and consistency.

I will make you laugh with my cheerful spirits, and cuddle with you for long naps after playtime. I love my blanket and my pillow, and I know not to jump on furniture.

I love to play but I can play a bit rough because I don’t know my strength when I get excited. I will chase after anything that moves fast (so cats are not a safe housemate for me). I also need to be reminded not to nip or lick when I get stressed or overjoyed. I am very enthusiastic and scent driven, so I like to look for treasures in your dirty laundry hamper or unattended trash cans if you leave them out because who doesn’t like a scavenger hunt, right? 

I like older children, and I am fine around them, but I am too big and goofy to be safely left alone with someone not mature or big enough to give me boundaries.

Similarly, I don’t dislike other dogs, but sometimes other dogs don’t like me, since I don’t always have the best doggie manners with my peers. I don’t initiate fights, but I don’t listen to them when they tell me to back off: I won’t take their  “growl” as a NO or let them get in my way if there is something I covet.  Therefore, I won’t do well with another alpha dog with a strong personality or another dog I have to compete with.   I am fine with laid back dogs who don’t mind that I get my way, but I don’t do well with competition at all.

Because I was deprived of things when I lived in the street, I have strong survival instincts, and I always want to be the first to get my human’s attention, get that toy or that piece of food before everyone else, and other pets don’t like that I don’t wait my turn, or that I ignore their body language if they are scared or angry.  So my lack of doggie manners with playmates have led to some misunderstandings and fights. I am not straight out aggressive with other dogs. I enjoy them if they don’t try to boss me around, but I am known not back down if there is confrontation.

Humans are my favorite thing in the world, and I will be your shadow, and be your best buddy everywhere you go.  There is nothing I like more than to be indoors with you and if you have an extra blanket to tuck me in, I will wrap in it, and nap next to you and enjoy the spoiled life. However I love camping and hiking, or just hanging out with you in the yard. I have as much fun inside as I do outside but I need a tall fence if you take me in the yard because I am smart, agile and crafty and I love to explore scents. Please know, I will need lots of hugs on the 4th of July and New Year’s Eve because I am terrified of fireworks, and of thunder. 

So if you are looking for an adventure companion or cuddle buddy, I will be your best friend for life, just know that I need clear boundaries and consistent communication to let me know how to be my best doggie-self.

A $300 adoption fee applies.

Meet Boeing! He is a four year old Beagle mix that is a very loyal, sweet and cuddly pup. He needs a little time to warm up to new people, but once he does he will be more than happy to sit and give you paw. He has with some resource guarding behavior, so children over the age of 13 for this boy. Boeing will need proper introductions to other dogs and will need someone to help him build confidence on taking walks and loud noises. You can also watch for stories, pictures and videos about me on our Facebook page https://www.facebook.com/groups/40103261297/ Ask to meet me today!!
 
Adoption fee: $375
 
Adoption fees for all dogs/puppies include a $50 refundable training deposit. Complete your basic training program and provide a copy of the certificate within 4 months (120 days) of adoption and we will refund $50 of the original adoption fee.
 
All dogs/puppies have been fully vetted including spay/neuter, micro-chipping, worming, heartworm testing and preventative treatment, flea/tick preventative, and all required age appropriate vaccinations. As required by Wisconsin Act 90, all dogs will have received a veterinarian exam (CVI) within the past 30 days.
 
Our adoption process requires the submission of an application. Applications and Adoption Rules can be found on our website, on the "HOW TO ADOPT" tab at JRsPupsNStuff.org. Upon receipt of the completed application, we will process the application including: contact with your veterinarian and completion of a home visit. Please be sure to include the contact information for your vet as we will call. If your vet requires an information release, please be sure to contact them as soon as you submit your application. We are a group of volunteers with families and jobs, so please be patient and allow a few days for our response.
 
JR's Pups-N-Stuff Dog Sellers License 270089-DS

animal.description:
(Le version française se trouve au https://www.sitwithme.ca/fr/dogs/miss-scarlett/) 

Miss Scarlett is looking for a foster or adoptive home.

Miss Scarlett

Boxer mix

4 years old

Female

 

Dogs: Maybe.  A really easy going and non-confrontational similar-sized pooch may be okay.  Meet and greet required and slow introductions.

Cats: No, thank you.

Kids: No, thank you. Too much for kids. 

Housing Type: A detached home only.  A townhome with someone home often and where loud barking could be okay. 

Fenced in yard: A fully fenced backyard or if in a country setting with no neighbours where she will not be left unattended or off leash outside.


Special: Someone eager to work with a trainer (virtually) to continue working on providing Scarlett the structure and confidence building she needs.  Scarlett is part of our RAD (Recovery Adoption Dogs) Program.  This means she will need a few meet and greets, her adoption trial is a month long and she will come with 3 training sessions included to ensure you have the tools to help Scarlett succeed in your home!  Calm home is KEY!  Must be in or near the Ottawa area due to meet and greets and for training support.

 

Scarlett is a very affectionate and very energetic dog, but she also has some difficulty understanding boundaries around personal space. She loves to and aims to please and wants to make her person happy… she just struggles with controlling her excitement – picture a dog having had too much coffee!  She came into care with swelling to her head and was tied out to a post.  It is possible that this injury could have caused her difficulty to settle but she has made so much progress.

 

Scarlett is a wonderful girl: happy, eager to please, sensitive and trusting. She loves to run and play in the fenced-in yard, whether it’s chasing a stick or ball or just expending her energy.  This is much needed as she has lots of energy to burn and would love an active person to share her days. She’s also equally happy to hang around the house and lounge with her favourite blanket or pillow. Whatever she’s doing, she loves to be near her human. Scarlett also likes her crate. She will often use it during the day and at night she is actually eager to “go to bed.” Once inside, she will thrash about for a few minutes, arguing with her blankets until she gets things just right for sleeping.

 

She is sensitive to heightened energy, movements and interaction from people. A calm household is the key!  She can be easily distracted and overstimulated which causes her anxiety. A chill home life with a predictable schedule that includes brain and body exercise would do her some good! She thrives when she has structure and predictability. She would love someone who will continue to work with her on her leash skills and is looking for a home life that has less visitors, with a fenced in yard and without neighboring dogs.  A country home without neighbours that does not have a fenced in yard would also work, so long as she was never left unattended or off leash. 

 

Scarlett can play with certain other dogs and has demonstrated that she can do this rather well but her meeting of dogs initially can be more challenging.  She is mostly non-confrontational in her approach, however, her level of energy can easily set off other dogs, and should the other dog react, there may be a conflict. Under the right supervision, she has the ability to play with many different kinds of dogs. Due to the current climate, and inability to work on complicated dog-dog introductions, we are seeking a pet-free home or an experience dog owner with a well matched dog for Miss Scarlett that is willing to meet near Ottawa for a meet and greet.

 

Scarlett responds best to positive and gentle reinforcement. She is so eager to please that it takes very little guide her. For example, if you just wait, she will sit when leaving the house, getting leashed up or eating her food. She looks up at you with those big brown eyes and it melts your heart. She does know some basic commands: sit, come, stay (sort of), bedtime. Your patience with  her needs will be so well rewarded.  She enjoys training time and is very engaging, making good eye contact, responding well to food-based training games and activities.

 

She is currently in board-and-train so is not only seeking a forever home, but would also welcome the opportunity for a dedicated foster home as well.   If you can foster her, please read the information on this page and then click APPLY NOW: http://www.sitwithme.ca/foster/

animal.description:
Hi there! My name is Boogie! I'm a very special girl, who needs a very special person. I absolutely love my human friends, but it can take me awhile to build that trusting relationship. I need someone willing to come visit with me several times before taking me home so we can build a strong relationship first. I get super wiggly and silly when I see my friends, so it's pretty easy to tell once I'm comfortable. I do need an adult only home where my person can provide a calm, stable environment for me. I'm a young girl, with energy to spare! I love to go for walks and hikes, car rides and I love playing with toys! I'm even getting pretty good at agility and I like to show off for my friends. I do like to play with other dogs, but it might not be the best fit for me to live with another dog in a home environment. 

Boogie came in as an owner surrender in August. She has been in a home or two, but none that met her needs long-term. She spends some of her days in a staff office, but mostly in her kennel. Boogie LOVES to be with people, it's something she wants more than anything. We see this dog struggling greatly in the shelter environment and want to give her the opportunity to find a family, but it is urgent for her - she is breaking down in the shelter environment each day that goes by. 

If you think I could be a good fit for your home and lifestyle, please reach out directly to lolson@highcountryhumane.org or jtasch@highcountryhumane.org for more info about me! I'm really looking for someone with lots of patience who can keep me safe in a home environment. 

My adoption fee is now fully sponsored thanks to generous donors!

animal.description:
Adira is being fostered in West Virginia. 

What we know about Adira:
*housebroken
*happy
*good with dogs
* good with people

What Adira's foster mom has to say about Adira:
Adira is an absolute joy. She is always so happy and has a zest for life like no other dog we’ve seen, especially with her circumstances. She was hit by a vehicle in October of 2020 and suffered severe eye trauma as a result, which required a double enucleation. In true Adira spirit, she didn’t let this get her down. She runs, plays, jumps and is completely housebroken! She loves people with all her heart. Be prepared for her to follow you literally everywhere. She has such an infectious personality and brings joy to everyone she meets. The Veterinary staff fell in love with her and even sent her with some extra peanut butter (her favorite!). Despite the vehicle incident, Adira is extremely healthy and all scarring has healed beautifully.
BDRA has voted against the use of electrical fencing effective immediately.

animal.description: Waffles is a beautiful, sweet 2 year old Black and Tan female that has made her way to a foster home in East Tennessee after being picked up as a stray. She has a few scuffs from her previous life, including some scars on her ears, and is tentative when meeting new people, but she warms up quickly. She is a bit underweight at 40 lbs but she is muscular and her coat is very shiny. Waffles is learning leashwalking, cratetraining ,and how to interact with other dogs in her foster home. She rides well in a car and rests quietly in her crate; she has had no crate accidents and reliably takes care of business outside in the fenced back yard when taken out. Waffles gets along well with the large mellow dogs in her foster home, but NO cats, please. Waffleâ€™s foster family is feeding her in her crate, as it seems she has been competing for nutrition, so is protective of her food. She is not yet tolerant of too much curiosity or excitement from other dogs and becomes very nervous if met with a rush of exuberance. Her foster parents can see her reservations diminishing rapidly and are confident that she will be a great addition to any family seeking a beautiful, sometimes tentative, and sweet house hound!

animal.description:
Hi, I'm Lovey Dovey! How are you doing? I'm doing great now, but I have had to get over a trauma of losing my best friend who had me since I was small. My owner was a veteran which I think is really admirable but then he broke his hip and was hospitalized and then through no fault of my own I ended up in the City Shelter. The good folks at Desert Haven helped me out of there and brought me here to live until I find my new family. 

I'm only about 9 months old so that's a lot of jostling around for a puppy but I have made it to safety now. Whew! I've even retained all my super cool and fun qualities through it all! You know what they say about youngens, we're resilient! Now, on to the next chapter of my life. 

Oh, you want to know some of those super cool and fun qualities I have? First of all, I love to play. I like to play with toys and play tug with people. I need a slow introduction to dogs and then I can do well and like to play and romp.  I'm gregarious and playful with my roommates here at Desert Haven.  I'm a little more of a mellow girl when it's just me and the humans (the volunteers who are taking care of me). So I have a nice balance to my winning personality. 

I'm also quite smart and already know how to "sit" when asked (hint: keep treats for me in your pocket). I'm still a puppy so I'll need to learn the ropes when I move in with you. Just let me know when I should pack my bags! Love you already, Lovey Dovey

(Lovey Dovey is around 35 pounds and we don't expect her to get too much bigger.)

animal.description: Hi, I'm Lincoln! I was originally adopted and now returned due to my previous owner's personal reason. I'm a fun-loving, energetic, goofy, and happy 4 1/2-year old, 55-pound brindle pittie mix, who loves playing fetch/tug of war with my favorite ball or rope, going on long walks, hiking and exploring new places, meeting new people, and when my energy is all expended, cuddling up with my humans. I am fully house-trained and know a full array of commands, such as Sit, Down, Stay, Come, Touch, Watch Me, Paw, Other Paw, and Drop It. I am adaptive, super friendly, loyal, and I brighten up the room with my infectious smile and goofy antics. I am neutered and up-to-date on all of my shots and vaccinations and have no health issues. My ideal home would be with experienced dog owners who are loving and active people that have the time and ability to take me on walks, runs, trips to the park, play, and give me lots of love and attention. While I currently live in Brooklyn, the big city sometimes stresses me out so I would do best somewhere a bit quieter with more space and access to a backyard, nearby park, or somewhere where I can run around freely! While I am good with most dogs and love running around with my other fur-friends, I would do best being the only dog in a household so I can get all the love and attention. I would do well in a home with older children or teenagers, but a home with young children, toddlers, or infants may not be best for me. I am very food-motivated and eager to please, so I'm very trainable and responsive to commands. I sometimes get triggered on a leash by skateboards or certain large dogs that antagonize me, so it's important to keep up with my training and maintain consistency so I don't get too rambunctious (distracting me with a treat and using the "Touch" command works wonders)! If you are interested in adopting me, please fill out the online application at https://amaanimalrescue.org/pet/lincoln-formerly-lucky/

animal.description:
Our feature tonight, a message about our special Star from her foster mom, the person who knows her the best.

“This girl ... so incredibly sweet. Star has many positive qualities! My favorite ... she greets all people enthusiastically, tries hard to please her humans and playing tug with her daddy, at every opportunity.  I want everyone to know even though Star has been here for a while there is nothing wrong with Star.  In fact, there is so much right!  She has solid obedience skills, loves to cuddle, is happy, smart and friendly.  As I wait for an appropriate adopter, one with a fenced yard, no young kiddos, someone who knows how (or is willing to learn) to manage behaviors that deal with resource guarding and a dog that has tendencies to overreact at the sight of new dogs that she has come so far from a few months ago.  I’m trying to share her behaviors with a positive spin, because Star is quite possibly the most happiest dog you could encounter.  She never has a bad day and is never in a bad mood.  Our family does the best we can, and we will continue to help Star be the best she can be.

I’m hoping there is a special heart out there who will see Star’s beautiful soul and give her the forever home she deserves.”

animal.description: A note from Nevile's foster family: Neville (we call him Nevi) is a sweet boy who enjoys taking walks and is good on a leash. He loves hanging out with his humans on the couch, bed or any comfy place. He often seeks out affection and attention and is always excited to greet his humans when they get home. He loves to be around people and is great company. He appreciates treats and takes them gently. Although Nevi is scared to get into cars and will try to avoid getting inside, he is fine on drives once inside. He should be picked up and placed inside the car until he becomes more comfortable when going for a drive. Nevi is very good with children and people in general. As to other animals, it is very important and highly recommended to have slow introductions between Nevi and other dogs in the home (we only have one male dog and do not know how he is towards female dogs and/or cats). When Nevi initially arrived in our home, there was an adjustment period between him and our resident dog. However, now they follow each other around all the time and have become good friends. Nevi would probably benefit from having a dog sibling so long as introductions are handled with patience and supervision. When walking him, he does pull towards other animals so that should be considered. Nevi doesn't like bath time and tries to be an escape artist from the tub/shower, but he seems excited to be clean afterwards. When we first welcomed Nevi into our home, he was limping on his back right paw, and he had x-rays performed of his right hip which reflected some broken bones. I don't want to misstate his condition so you should inquire about his medical history through the shelter if interested in adopting to make sure his health status will be a good fit for your lifestyle. He has had an opportunity to rest and recover in our home, and he hasn't been limping recently. This condition doesn't seem to slow him down, and he loves to run and play. We have been limiting/preventing him (post x-rays) from running, playing and jumping to make sure he has sufficient time to heal. Nevi is potty trained. He really is a wonderful dog who deserves to be in a loving forever home. Finally, if you adopt him, we would love to hear how he is doing and would welcome pictures if you are willing to share!

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.
Hi I'm Norman
I'm a goofy, energetic, athletic 4 year old American bull dog mix with lots of love and attention for the right person! I'm eager to please, always ready to play, love walks. I always get excited whenever I hear the sound of the keys for a walk! I'm 100% house trained and 100% crate trained, heartworm negative and up to date for all my shots.
Mama and Papa got me as a rescue. When they got me I was dog reactive and we started working with a trainer. Even though I've improved leaps and bounds, I'm finding that apartment living isn't for me. All the sights and sounds is leaving me a little too anxious. The trainer says I should be the only animal in a home with a fenced yard, so I have a lot of open space. I also shouldn't be with a home with small children.
The trainer also says I should have an experienced owner, with a firm hand ,who knows how to raise American bulldogs. I can be a stubborn guy, and although Mama and Papa love me very much, they know they can't give me what I need to the best I can be.
Can you be the one who can give me my best life?

P.S. Mama and Papa will provide my kennel, clothes food, and toys to help me transition to my next chapter.Contact Reg.c.evans@gmail.com with any questions and adoption inquires. ****Courtesy listing**** This dog is not the property of The Buster Foundation. Please direct all inquires to the email listed above.

animal.description:
Yuki is a 1-year old, relaxed and sweet girl. She showers us with kisses when we arrive home and is an overall very affectionate dog to "her people”. She also LOVES to play and to have her belly scratched. She is aloof with strangers and needs time with you to get acquainted and be your friend.

Despite being calm and relaxed around the house, she does have puppy energy when she's outside and loves to sprint around the yard. She would love to be in an active family where she can play off leash (in a large fenced in yard). She was not leash trained when we got her but has quickly made great strides, is very responsive to treats and has learned basic commands very quickly. 

She seems to be playful with other dogs, but can be dominant in her play. She is best suited for a home without small children or cats.

Yuki was adopted from the Humane Society after being found as a stray in a local park. We have fallen in love with her since arriving in our home, but unfortunately she is not compatible with our cats.


Yuki’s family have asked that any interested adopters first complete an adoption application. 

The adoption application can be downloaded at this page: https://tikihutakitarescue.com/adopting  

Please email your completed adoption applications to:  info@tikihutakitarescue.com

animal.description:
Wiley is a handsome adult male Pit Bull Terrier mix who was brought to the HSOV on March 6, 2020 by Good Samaritans who found him on Briggs Hill Road in the Belpre Ohio area.

Wiley has a brown/brindle-and-white short smooth coat, a long tail, and a beautiful white face with a small patch of brindle around his right eye and a large patch of brindle at the base of his right ear. He has a rather slender muzzle, a black button nose, and short semi-erect ears.

Wiley was a very frightened boy being confined in a kennel when he first entered our shelter and was not a happy camper for the first few weeks with us ? We had hoped that his owner would see the preliminary photos we took on March 8th or that someone will recognize him but, sadly, that did not happen. Wiley was most likely a very different dog in his home with a family who loved him.

Wiley weighs approximately 55-60 lbs and has already been neutered.

In compliance with the Ohio Revised Code, Wiley was held for three days so that his owner would have an opportunity to come and reclaim him with proof of ownership but that happy reunion did not take place.

Wiley is beginning to warm up to our kennel techs and, though he is still nervous in our shelter, Wiley is showing us more of his personality. He will obey the 'sit' command, so someone in his past has spent time training him to recognize that word. Wiley also loves treats and appears to be an intelligent boy.

These updated photos were taken on March 22, 2020 when Wiley accompanied two of our core volunteers whom he has learned to trust. He was still a bit cautious of the 'paparazzi' following him and snapping photos but nice to that lady just the same. Wiley loved the 'good boy' treats which were offered to him in reward for good behavior.

Wiley is full of athletic energy, and we’d love to see him in action on a trampoline since he appears to have natural acrobatic skills.

Wiley would do best with an experienced handler and an ‘alpha’ leader who could provide guidance/training so that Wiley could reach his full potential. Our kennel techs would be happy to introduce you to Wiley and to share their experiences/knowledge about him.

animal.description: Sasha is a 7 year old 55lb spayed female Pit Bull Terrier/Beagle mix. She came to us as an owner surrender due to her thriving best in a home with no other dogs or young children. She was a little shy at first, but has come out of her shell and is very friendly and cuddly with staff here at the shelter. She is a quiet girl that enjoys relaxing and snacks... the perfect Netflix partner! She is heartworm positive. This is a curable condition and cannot be passed directly to other animals. She qualified for a 30% off voucher through our Have-A-Heart program. We are open by appointment only to ensure we can properly social distance here at the shelter. We cannot guarantee a specific pet or type of pet will be available at your appointment. We do not hold pets. We operate on a first come first serve basis and while you can put what/who you are interested in in the appointment sign up, all appointments are general dog/cat/other animal appointments since we cannot guarantee what will be available at the time of your appointment. If you would like to set up a non-specific dog or cat appointment we have our scheduling system online now at: https://guilfordcountync.gov/our-county/animal-services/animal-shelter/animal-adoption-scheduling All adopted cats and dogs at Guilford County Animal Services come fully up to date on age appropriate vaccines, spayed/neutered, and microchipped. If you are interested in meeting any of our pets, please visit our website to schedule an appointment online. If you believe this may be your pet, please come to the shelter during business hours and bring your ID, proof of ownership, and proof of spay/neuter and/or rabies vaccination history if you have it. See our reclaiming your pet page for more information. If you have any further questions, please contact us at 336-641-3400 or visit our website at https://guilfordcountync.gov/our-county/animal-services/animal-shelter. Thank you for your interest in helping the animals of Guilford County!

animal.description:
Chester is very sweet, easy going, and affectionate. He is a fan favorite of the other dogs on the premises. He is social and get along with everyone. In fact, the puppies and small males think he is the bomb. 

He has very interesting coloring which I have never seen before. He looks like a yellow lab with a dark brown saddle and gradient coloring between the two with a bob tail that wiggles constantly

Chester is crate trained, and when he’s had enough of being affectionately mauled by the other dogs, he likes to go rest in his crate. He likes being outside, but spends a lot of his time in his igloo.

Chester, and his sister Maya, spent the first two years of their lives being neglected and abused and kept on a lot with very little interaction and no shelter. So he now thinks that shelter is amazing and that human and friendly dog interaction is great! 

Chester has never shown any signs of aggression of any kind, including food aggression. He can be fed freely together with other animals.

Chester is used to playing with the other dogs on the property. He is well socialized, both with humans and dogs. While I have never seen him interact with a cat, I have no reason to anticipate a problem.

************************************
ADOPTION INFORMATION 
************************************
I only adopt LOCALLY; San Diego and immediate vicinity. No long distance. Certainly no out of state.

I cannot respond to questions as to whether the animal is available. The minute the animal is adopted, or intended for a specific person, I change the status of the dog to adopted or adoption pending or hold. Please DO NOT contact me asking if the animal is available. If the dog is listed as adoptable, it is available. 

A home check and a background check are MANDATORY to be considered. If you are unable or unwilling to consent to these requirements, please do not apply,

Preference will be given to individuals who follow the instructions AND provide complete information for adoption purposes. 

1) Please go to our website ( http://aaofus.org/adoption-application.html )

animal.description:
Hard to believe but after owning Charlie Brown and his companion canine Leyla, their senior owner asked his daughter to euthanize both dogs because he didn’t want them anymore. Fortunately his daughter cared enough about these two lovable pets to bring them to AALOC.

Charlie Brown is about a 15-pound poodle mix. When he arrived Charlie Brown needed extensive dental care, ultimately losing 17 of his 42 teeth because of decay and neglect. He also had a skin condition that required veterinarian attention. Both of these issues have been addressed and Charlie Brown is now looking for a new home and a forever family. We do recommend an adult only home for Charlie Brown and one without other pets since he likes to be the center of attention.

You can tell Charlie Brown was loved for a long time. He makes friends easily with other dogs and humans alike. Charlie Brown is a little older but has plenty of love to give in return, and although Charlie Brown has always been with Leyla, he is available as a single dog adoption.

Poodles are one of the most intelligent and trainable dogs. One thing to consider: The coat of a poodle is tight and curly because the hair does not generally shed out. This means that Charlie Brown would need to be groomed regularly, otherwise his fur will mat to itself, a painful condition that can lead to skin problems. 

Please submit an application to adopt Charlie Brown at www.AALOC.org. Once your application is reviewed and approved we will contact you to make an appointment to visit us at AALOC to meet Charlie Brown during visiting hours (10am to 3pm daily) and get to know him a bit.

Donation of $165 for dog adoption includes spay/neuter, vaccinations, and a microchip. Applications require a veterinary reference and home visit (in Orange County, CA). animal.description:
Meet Ramba! This gorgeous girl lost her home in Lake Charles, Louisiana during the devastation of Hurricane Laura. This category 4 hurricane with 140 mph winds caused mass destruction to the area and Ramba’s foster lost her home. Ramba is now safe in Texas with a new foster.

This Southern Belle can’t wait to relocate to the Pacific Northwest! Ramba is currently in Houston and will arrive in Washington on October 28th and is available for adoption or foster directly off of transport. To apply, please fill out an application at www.doggedly.org/adoption-app
 
Ramba is 55lbs and 3 years old. She is super friendly, outdoorsy, athletic and loves to explore. She would make an amazing running buddy and would love to go on some scenic hikes in nature. This girl is friendly, confident and enjoys the company of humans. Her biggest motivator is praise and affection! This girl is such a people pleaser and wants to constantly be by her human’s side and told that she’s a good girl!
 
Ramba is not only stunning, but she is dog, cat and kid friendly. Ramba enjoys the company of other dogs, but is very independent. She is low key and respectful around other dogs, sniffing them and then paying other dogs no mind. Ramba enjoys the company of other dogs and is extremely pleasant on walks, car rides and social outings, but is very human oriented. She enjoys the company of humans the most and would love to be the only dog in a home to soak up all of your attention! When meeting a cat, Ramba acknowledged and then ignored the cat, glancing up to her human handler for direction. Ramba has excellent recall and was easily redirected, although she was excited to meet the cat. As per any introduction to indoor cars, a controlled, slow introduction should be followed.

Ramba is a medium energy dog that is highly intelligent. Beautiful Ramba will require a home that can accommodate her needs both physically and mentally. This girl is a thinker and loves to please her humans. She would thrive in a home environment that would keep her on her toes with plenty of brain games, training and mental enrichment to challenge her. Mental stimulation helps Ramba to relax and she enjoys being given commands to follow. Ramba knows her basic commands such as sit and will sit pretty for a treat! She is a dream on a leash and is perfectly well behaved walking on busy city sidewalks. Not much bothers Ramba! She is also house broken and crate trained, although she doesn’t love to be kenneled for long periods of time alone, probably due to the sudden change of environment after the hurricane. Ramba has adjusted quickly in a new foster home, and being with people has been a huge comfort to her! She much prefers a comfy dog bed with a puzzle toy or bone to keep her busy. Ramba is totally content snuggling up on the couch while hanging out at home, as long as her exercise needs are met!

Though we do our best in trying to answer all emails in a timely manner, sometimes things get away from us, get lost or misplaced. Sandy Brown, Director, PAW Animal Shelter

animal.description:
Biffy and Coventry are a bonded pair living in a foster home. Submit an application from our website and then make an appointment to meet them.

Biffy (male) and Coventry (female) are not eligible for foster and will be a straight adoption.

Age: ~8 years
Weight: Coventry is aboutt 62lbs, Biffy is about 68lbs
Housebroken: Yes
Crate trained: They have not been crated, but they have done well with free roam while they have been left solo.
Dog sociability: They love each other and are required to be adopted together. They can sometimes resource guard food from each other, but it is manageable. They haven't had too much interaction with other dogs. 
Cat sociability: Unknown
Kids: Friendly! They live with a kid in their foster home and have been doing great. 
Ideal home: Buffy and Coventry are a super sweet senior duo looking for a comfy home that can continue to keep up with their medical needs (explained below). They will take some time to decompress and management may be needed at times between the two dogs, so an adopter who can read dog body language would be great!

Biffy is a true southern gentlemen. His BFF is his sister, Coventry, with whom he has a typical sibling relationship: one minute he's wrestling and playing with her, later he's not happy she's decided to nap in his bed. He is very polite and a wonderful guy all around. Loves people, adults and kids, loves pets and scratches, and attention but isn't constantly demanding. He's always ready to go for a walk, long or short, sidewalk or park and loves walks so much he dances and prances for the first minute or so of being on his leash. He walks right beside you and doesn't lunge or pull. He loves being outside in our yard sleeping in the sun when it's warm and likes to hang out by the front gate where he can people and dog watch. He can be a bit barky at dogs who bark at him first at the fence, but he responds very well to redirection. 

Coventry is a sensitive and sweet southern belle who loves her brother and BFF Biffy. She loves to wrestle and run with him but will let him know when he's displeased her by going by her food bowl, or pushing his way in to get pets. Coventry is the braver of the two dogs when trying something new like jumping into and out of the car, or trying out a long staircase. Coventry comes great when called and knows "go to your bed" and does so when asked. She also knows "go to your spot" in the yard when let out to go to the bathroom. She prefers privacy when she going to the bathroom because she's a real lady. She's a little sensitive to quick moves, loud voices or noises of something being dropped but this is lessening as she decompresses. She is easily walked with Biffy. And she does love her walks, neighborhoods, grassy parks, forest preserves she loves walks of all kinds.She also likes her tennis ball and will retrieve it. She will also throw the ball up in the air and then run after it!

Coventry has kidney disease, and takes daily medication along with a lifelong prescription diet. She will need monitoring bloodwork an estimated 1-2 times per year. She had some issues with incontinence on arrival which have resolved with the medication and food interventions. We recommend her adopter to monitor with regular vet. 

Both Biffy and Coventry tested positive for heartworm disease at their prior shelter and received treatment there. They will need to be on exercise restriction for the next 6 months until they can be retested for heartworm disease. If their 6 month retests comes back positive, OTAT will cover treatment at our Ellis Clinic.

Biffy and Coventry's combined adoption fee is 150. They are each spayed/neutered, up to date on core vaccines, microchipped and heartworm positive. As large breed senior dogs, both Biffy and Coventry have arthritis and are on joint supplements daily. 

***We are receiving a much higher than usual number of adoption applications. We ask that you please be patient and someone will be in touch via email within 72 hours. Please do not email us unless you have not received a response in 72 hours. Please only fill out one adoption application. ***

animal.description:
****Please do not send us inquiries/emails asking if this dog is still available; if a dog/puppy is still listed on Petfinder, we are still accepting applications for them. See the bottom of this bio for more FAQs regarding our adoption process before emailing.****

Name: Jax

Age: 4 yrs (DOB 11/8/16)

Current Weight: 16 lbs

Rescued from: Texas

Hi, I'm Jax! I used to live with me mom, dad and little brother but my family had to move into an apartment and I tend to bark if I hear anything out of the ordinary, so they couldn't keep me anymore :( I would love to live in a house again so I can run and play in the yard! I am potty trained and know how to use a doggy door. I can be a little shy/timid when I first meet new people or go to new places, but once I warm up I am a little lovebug! I have an independent side and am full of personality! 

Jax will be arriving at SNARR's Adoption Center in Brewster, NY soon ready for adoption!  His ideal home would include a fenced-in yard, and he does prefer a home without young children or large dogs.

IMPORTANT: This dog has not yet been altered. For any dog or puppy that is not able to be spayed/neutered prior to adoption, SNARR requires a $125 deposit in addition to your adoption fee, as well as a signed Spay/Neuter Contract stating you will have this dog altered within 6 months of adoption. The $125 deposit will be returned once the contract has been fulfilled. 

Health: up to date on required vaccines, will be microchippped upon arrival to NY

Adoption fee: $375

To apply to adopt Jax, fill out an application at www.snarrnortheast.org/applications. 


-------------------------------------------------------
FAQs -- PLEASE READ ALL BEFORE EMAILING

**Please note that SNARR NE is a volunteer-based organization. While our volunteers will try to respond to you as quickly as possible, it is helpful if you review the following information about our adoption process before emailing:**

- LISTED BREED(S) & AGE: We are taking our best guess on age, breed, and size when fully grown, based on the puppy's/dog's physical appearance and what we might have learned about one or both parents depending on the situation. *NOTE* We rarely know a dog's exact age, nor are we able to tell the true or full breed mix of dogs as our information is limited most of the time. Because we often do not have access to medical records at the time that we are posting dogs to Petfinder, there are sometimes discrepancies between what is posted on Petfinder and what might be listed on a dog's medical records.

- SNARR'S ADOPTION PROCESS: The first step in adopting or meeting a SNARR dog/puppy is to fill out an application at www.snarrnortheast.org/applications. Once we receive your application, one of our adoption application processors will contact you, review our adoption process with you, and answer any additional questions you may have. **We do not go on a first-come-first-serve basis for adoptions, but on best fit for a family and most importantly the puppy or dog.**

- MEETING ADOPTABLE DOGS: Meet and greets will not be scheduled until after your adoption application has been fully processed by one of our adoption processors.

- APPLYING ONLINE: If you fill out an online application, please do so from a computer (not a mobile device), make sure you answer ALL the questions in as much detail as possible, and that you receive a confirmation email. If you do not receive a confirmation email, that means we did NOT receive your application.

- PUPPIES: We do suggest listing a 1st, 2nd and 3rd choice on your application if applying for a puppy with several litter mates.

- ADOPTION FEES:  $495 for puppies / $375 for adults. Adoption Fees for Seniors, Special Needs and Bonded Pairs vary

animal.description:
Morganna is a sweet, demure girl who will do best in an affectionate, warm, and loving home. She can be shy at first, but with continued patience, she eventually comes out of her shell and will not leave your side! As days went on, we began to see her true personality shine through. Morganna is a playful and easygoing girl who is eager to please and loves affection. She can be cautious with other dogs and new people at first, but will warm up if they are just as friendly and playful as her! Morganna gets along great with our two resident pups (a 7-month old and five-year-old, both males), enjoys snuggling, and is doing superbly on walks (with continued practice she will be a great hiking sidekick!).

Loud noises do throw her off a bit so we're unsure how she would do in a household with small children. Morganna is also house trained (we've had no accidents!) and she does OK in her crate, although she prefers roaming freely (and has not exhibited any destructive behaviors or separation anxiety). She is a pure sweetheart and will be an excellent addition to a loving home that will give her the time and patience to come out of her shell and grow into her confident self.

animal.description:
Meet Giselle!

Sweet and curious, good-natured and friendly with dogs and people, this pup is looking for the simple things in life. Giselle is a four-year-old terrier mix that is polite and shy. Likely dumped by her previous owner she was found with heartworms, missing fur and skin and was in generally poor condition. Despite all these issues she's a calm, sweet girl.

Highly trainable and easy to please she sits nicely for treats and loves to be petted. She's potty trained, sleeps in a crate, walks on a leash and is good with pets. She knows come and sit. She's a little apprehensive when being approached by people she doesn't know but seems to warm up quickly to them.

Giselle needs to lose some weight and will need thyroid medicine for the rest of her life. (average cost $30 per month) Giselle is just waiting for that special person who can help her become her best self. If you are that person, please apply at pawsinthecity.org today!

For adoption information or to complete an application, please go to: http://www.pawsinthecity.org/adopt.htm

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.Meet Andy! He is a 15lbs Shih Tzu mix with an approximate DOB of May 2013. Its a good thing that Andy is so cute because he does have some troubling behaviors.

Andy was found in the woods completely matted, dirty and starving. He was originally thought to be 10+ years old but the vet said he was a bit younger than that. We may never really know his true age. Due to many years of no real socialization, he is reactive to many things.

To be very upfront, Andy is very defensive and will bite due to fear. He does not like new people, loud noises and most dogs. This means his adopter needs to be a single person or a couple with no kids and no dogs. He gets along with the current foster's cat by basically ignoring her.

His foster mom has built trust with Andy since his arrival to Wags in June 2020 and he will now sit on her lap and accept affection from the whole family. Together, Andy and foster mom have been working hard with a trainer. Andy is food motivated, which is great! He now knows how to sit and is becoming less reactive. Andy is easily startled and continues to growl and snap daily. His adopter needs to be willing to learn his triggers (gloved hands, food bowls, etc...) and be able to back away quickly, in order to give him his space.

Andy is a long haired dog that hates being groomed (brushed, cut or bathed). He bites anyone who tries. This means he can not go to the groomers. He must be completely sedated at the vets to be groomed.

Andy also hates the vet. He must be sedated to be examined or treated. He has dry eyes and requires eye drops 3xs a day but will not allow anyone to put them in. Andy had his left eye removed because it was constantly infected even after multiple antibiotic treatments. He is doing fine with just one eye. He will lose the right eye if he does not learn to accept the drops. Andy will take oral medication when it is placed in his food.

On a more positive note, Andy loves car rides, time outside in fenced yard and being near his foster mom. He would ideally like a home with a yard to run in but it is not a must. He does the most adorable "happy dance" when foster mom comes back into the house. Andy has learned to be very affectionate on his terms. Adopter needs to be ready to let Andy take his time adjusting to new home and know that this may be a few month process of ups and downs for all involved. We are hoping there is a special person out there that will provide a home for Andy to live out his days comfortably and take things at his own pace. Interested in adopting this lovable animal? Please go to our website www.wagsmn.org and fill out an Adoption Application. Once the application is processed, a Wags representative will contact you, answer any questions you may have, and set up a time/location for a meet and greet! A home visit is required prior to adoption.

Thank you for choosing to adopt!

Breed and temperament determination: Wags & Whiskers Animal Rescue attempts to determine breed and temperament using a combination of looks, information provided to us at intake, and our experience with the animal while in our Rescue. We do not guarantee this determination.

animal.description:
Meet our Charlie Fairstret, a 9-year-old male Boston Terrier, up to date on vaccines, neutered, microchipped and HW negative. Charlie is an owner surrender so we know his history. The owners were changing lifestyle and, unfortunately, Charlie was unable to be part of that.
He is a big boy at 33 lbs, robust, playful, crate-trained and totally housebroken. Most notably about Charlie is his strong personality! He is no shrinking violet of a dog that sleeps his life away, not Charlie! He is endearingly quirky, curious, very vocal, headstrong and smart. But he is also sensitive and affectionate. He wants to be where the action is! He is a powerful guy and probably would not be good for small children or frail adults. He will pull on a leash, for example. He does not get along with other dogs or cats, so he needs to be a solo pet. He is fine with humans of various ages and gender.
He is good in the car, on walks, at the vet. He is fearful of loud noises. We haven't had a thunderstorm with Charlie around yet, but he doesn't like fireworks and we have been told he is afraid of loud storms.
Charlie, like many dogs and people, takes a while to get comfortable in a new environment but his unique personality and traits are being revealed more and more every day. If you would like to know more about Charlie, contact his foster mom, Sally, in Augusta, GA at (706)414-7667. Charlie's adoption fee is $250.00 We prefer homes with prior Boston Terrier experience and current pet history. The process always begins with an application found at: www.bostonterriertn.org
NOTE: Submission of an application and fee does not guarantee adoption of any specific Boston, since that particular dog may have applications pending or may not be the right match for you.
Please use the foster momma or dad's contact information above for questions.
The process always begins with an application which can be found at The Boston Terrier Rescue of East Tennessee website
Note that in most cases, we do not adopt to families with small children, e.g., 'under 6,' as a precaution to the child's safety and the dog's safety. In some cases with larger Boston mixes or other dogs, we do make exceptions. Please ask the foster momma.
We prefer to place dogs within driving distance of where they are being fostered. If someone from outside the local area is approved for adoption, they must be willing to personally drive/fly to get the dog. The East Coast division (NC/SC/VA/MD/DC) does have special transport capabilties for their kids. Ask them.
Also, submission of an application and fee does not guarantee adoption of any specific Boston since that particular dog may have applications pending or may not be the right match for you.

animal.description:
Ali is approximately 4 years old and 68 lbs. Ali is a happy-go-lucky boy that loves to get all the attention.  He enjoys chewing on toys but you will need a lot of stuffed toys as he loves to de-stuff them in record time.  Ali loves to play and is very active. He would do best in a home with older kids as he will unintentionally knock them over.  Are you ready for a big, lovable goof?  Then Ali might just be your boy.

The adoption fee of $175 includes the spay/neuter, rabies vaccine, distemper/parvo combination vaccine, bordetella vaccine, deworming, heartworm test, heartworm preventative, flea preventative, and a microchip.

To inquire about this dog, please select the Ask About button; include information about your family, what you are looking for in a dog, and your phone number; and select the Send Email button.  Do NOT call our center. We usually respond via email within 24-48 hours; please check your spam folder if you don't hear from us.

Often there is very little known about our dogs' and puppies' history or even current habits. We are best guessing on breed blends. We can't guarantee there is or isn't a specific breed in their breed blend.

You can always expect to do training, regardless of whether you adopt a dog or a puppy, including crate training, house training, and basic manners. Expect a 10+ year financial, physical, and emotional commitment to this canine. We provide a variety of materials and resources to assist you with this. All dogs and especially puppies are a lot of work and a long financial commitment. Please research what it means to have a dog and make sure a dog is still going to be an important part of your life in 10-15 years. All dogs and puppies need a lot of patience and guidance.

Most dogs who are in shelters will need an adjustment period after adoption. No matter how nice our shelter is and how much attention they get from our volunteers, it is not a home and they will need time to acclimate and get rid of some nervous energy.

animal.description: Weddo is a super handsome boy with one beautiful, icy blue eye. Weddo is deaf, so he's an excellent road trip companion- he won't care about what music you choose, or notice when you butcher the lyrics! When meeting other dogs in PACC playgroup, Weddo was appropriate and tolerant when greeting the other pups, and was playful and social. Still, we recommend a meet-and-greet for any resident dogs (everyone should meet a potential roommate before going home with them.) He was also reportedly housebroken during a brief adoption. Weddo's hearing impairment doesn't affect his day to life, but he can be easily startled so is looking for a home with no young children who might sneak up on him. Here's what a volunteer had to say about this special boy: Weddo was sound asleep in this kennel despite the usual morning chaos. I was careful not to startle him, but no need to worry. He was friendly, ready to go, leashed easily and marched out the door. We walked around the big lake- a lovely walk- no reaction to other dogs or people. A great way to start a morning! Ask Weddo's volunteer advocate, Gail, about him: foster070204@gmail.com Check out the basic obedience signs he's learning!: tinyurl.com/weddosignals WEDDO IS ENROLLED IN THE GOOD DOG PROJECT AT PACC - Read a message from his case manager here: tinyurl.com/gdpmessage - Ask his case manager about him: rachel.jones@pima.gov

He's super shy at first but warms up after about a few days. He is used to being around other dogs.
He is very weary about being around fast moving children and will ignore them as long as they ignore him. He would not do well in a house with a child who wants to get in his face.
Since he is still getting used to new things he will require a lot of TLC to get him used to his new home, but after that we feel like Lincoln would be a great addition to a household.
As his foster parents we have seen a lot of improvement over the month we have had him. We feel like he would continue to get better given even more time.
After the first week in his foster home he has shown he loves belly rubs and attention.
He does well with being free-fed and shows no signs of food aggression or resource guarding.
He is very shy during meet and greets and stands still in fear while potential adopters meet him, but he lets them pet him, also standing still.

We hope you agree and understand that our goal to find the best forever home is our #1 priority! Please fill out an Adoption Application at https://underdogrescueofflorida.com/

animal.description:
My name is CAMILLA and I'm a darling 10 yr F Yorkie. I'm 11 lbs of PURE SWEETNESS. I was given up by my owner due to NO TIME. I'm completely BLIND, but you would never know it because  I get around just fine with my sense of smell. Sometimes I get into trouble because my nose leads me to any and all food left out and I've stolen sandwiches and snacks left behind and ripped open trash bags. I need a human who has had a blind dog before or who has the patience/compassion to learn about what a blind dog needs. Other than being blind, I'm super sweet, affectionate, silly, curious little girl and friendly to all I "smell". I've met a cat and was fine with it so I can be with a cat as long as it's fine with me. It's best if I go with older kids ages 12 Yrs + that know how to respect my special needs. I am partially housebroken and do my business both outside and inside on pads. I used to live with another small dog but we had a love/hate relationship and it was best to part ways, but I get lonely every once in a while. That said, I would love to be with another dog to be my "helper" dog but it would have to be the "right" dog.  I'm very special and an absolute LITTLE GEM and deserve to be the "apple of someone's eye" and spoiled rotten. I want to be your co-pilot and go on all your adventures. 

For more info/application - please email: INFO@TAILSOFLOVERESCUE.ORG
