animal.description:
******Please read this entire post & read her adoption requirements****
Ears for days, absolutely stunning & sassier then sassy, everyone meet- #GracieLou. She’s a 7 year old #FrenchBulldog who can be a troublemaker at times, but the biggest lover at the same time. Gracie needs a calm laidback home and only wants love on her own terms- so she’s basically a cat. She loves to lounge around all day and enjoys her daily walks. Gracie Lou loves to play and can be very vocal. 

Gracie loves to taunt and chase the cat currently in her foster home, but we catch them cuddling on the bed sometimes together. She’s great with other dogs her size or bigger, but can be dog selective and can be an instigator at times. Gracie is 100% potty trained (Will pee when not watched), 100% crate trained and great on a leash. 

***ADOPTION REQUIREMENTS: NO EXCEPTIONS***
*** Gracie needs an experienced dog owner who knows how to handle and work with a reactive dog. We will not adopt her out to a first time pet owner.
*** Gracie would thrive best with a single owner 
*** Gracie does have a bite history!
*** Gracie needs consistent structure and must be crated when the owner isn't home. When she is coddled, she take control of the home. She needs an experienced pet owner.
*** No kids under 18 (No exceptions) so if you’re planning to have kids anytime in the next 6-8 years please don’t waste your time applying.
*** Gracie can be reactivate when she doesn't get her way. She needs an experienced dog owner who can understand her verbal and nonverbal communication.
 
Adoption Fee & Medical:
Gracie is currently up for adoption through Lending A Helping Paw Dog Rescue. Her adoption fee is $350 and will include his Distemper, Lepto, Parvo, Bordetella, Rabies, Deworming, Fecal Test, Microchip & her spay. Gracie is heartworm negative, has had her proheart 6 injection and is on flea and tick prevention.

We kindly ask that you please wait to ask any questions until the phone interview.

***PLEASE READ THIS ENTIRE POST & FOLLOW THE INSTRUCTIONS***

With the Covid-19 Pandemic going on we are still doing adoptions, but  please remember that we are all volunteers and safety comes first. All prospective adopters must live within the state of #Michigan.  Please remember we are not a shelter and are 100% foster based. Once you submit your application, it may take up to 2 weeks for us to get back to you. So please be patient with us.

Again, we kindly ask that you please read the entire post to answer your questions. If you cannot follow the instructions properly, we will skip your application or request and move onto the next one. We kindly ask that you save any questions, comments or concerns for the phone interview. We kindly ask the following:
No phone calls, No pm's, & No multiple emails- We are all volunteers and promise to get back to you within a timely fashion! 
 
Lending A Helping Paw Dog Rescue; previously known as the PRO-PET-OTIC Foundation, is a 100% Foster-Based Rescue that is ran by all Volunteers. Which means that we are not a shelter & each animal is in an actual home with a foster family. We kindly ask that you put any questions within the email & our team of Volunteers will get back to you. With the overwhelming amount of emails please be patient with our 100% volunteer family and we will get back to you. The application MUST BE filled out, a Vet Check MUST BE completed by our team, as well as a phone interview before we do a 'Meet N Greet.' You must be 21 years old to apply.
 
Vet Checks:
When adopting through our rescue, we 'ALWAYS' do a vet check on each applicant's pets that they have owned over the past 10 years. Please make sure to call your vet to grant them permission to release this information to our rescue. That being said, all of the animals in each applicant's home must be UTD on all of their vaccines (DHLPP & Rabies), an UTD Heartworm Test, & currently on both Flea & Tick, as well as Heartworm Prevention. So please make sure that when you are applying that all of your current animals go to the vet that is listed.
 
How To Apply:
If you're interested in adopting one of our available dogs:
1. Email LendingAHelpingPaw313@gmail.com with the dogs name as the subject when you ask for the adoption application.
2. Once you have completed the application, please print it out, fill it out, scan it, & then email it back to LendingAHelpingPaw313@gmail.com.
3. Please make sure to call your vet to grant our organization permission to do a vet check on your current pet.
4. Please be honest & truthful on your application. We always do a 'Vet Check.' We always do a 'Home Visit.' And we always have both the prospective families & dogs best interest at heart!
 
Lending A Helping Paw Mission Statement:
Our mission is to play an active role throughout our community by 'Lending A Helping Paw' to animals that were either abandoned, in shelters, unwanted, homeless, chained outdoors, or victims of prior abuse and/or neglect. Our rescue family has accomplished this by setting up each animal and their new families up for success, educating and consulting pet parents about what's in the best interest of their pets overall well-being, and creating an awareness in our community about the vital importance of fully vetting and spaying & neutering their pets.
 
Where Can You See The Rest Of Our Pack?
All of our adoptable dogs can be found on our Facebook group at:
https://www.facebook.com/groups/LendingAHelpingPaw/
 
Thank you in advance,
The Lending A Helping Paw Dog Rescue Family

animal.description:
Up for #Adoption in Metro #Detroit
This is what #Perfection looks like! And they say that Models aren't smart! Just look at this #Gorgeous, #Smart & #Talented girl right here. Yep that's right! Our baby girl #Micah knows how to #Smile on command ?. This beautiful baby girl is up for adoption through Lending A Helping Paw Dog Rescue. Check out her bio below:

Corky, silly & sweet, ladies & gentleman we're excited to introduce Micah. She's a 4-5 year old #Rottweiler mix. Micah enjoys long walks, spending time with her humans & loves cuddle time. She does okay with other male dogs when properly introduced, but can be selective and it's mainly with female dogs. She's non reactive to cats, but hasn't been up close and interacted with one yet. Micah is now officially 100% crate trained, 100% potty trained & does phenomenal on a leash. We'd recommend no children 10 & under. Although she is great with all people and craves human companionship along with tons of attention, Micah does like her own personal space. She knows all of her basic commands and is just a lover at the end of the day.

Adoption #Requirements: No Exceptions
- Fenced in Yard Required
- No kids under the age of 10
- No Female Dogs
- Would thrive best as the only dog
Micah is currently up for adoption through Lending A Helping Paw Dog Rescue. Her adoption fee is $350 & will include her distemper, rabies, bordetella, parvo, & lepto vaccines; deworming; microchip; heartworm test; fecal test & being fixed. Micah is currently on both flea & tick, as well as heartworm prevention. We kindly ask that you please wait until then to ask any questions.

***PLEASE READ THIS ENTIRE POST & FOLLOW THE INSTRUCTIONS****
 
With the Covid-19 Pandemic going on we are still doing adoptions, but please remember that we are all volunteers and safety comes first. With our rescue being based in the Metro Detroit area, all prospective adopters must live within the state of Michigan (which means No out of state adoptions). Please remember we are not a shelter and are 100% foster based. Once you submit your application, it may take up to 2 weeks for us to get back to you. So please be patient with us.

Again, we kindly ask that you please read the entire post to answer your questions. If you cannot follow the instructions properly, we will skip your application and move onto the next one. We kindly ask that you save any questions, comments or concerns for the phone interview. We kindly ask the following: No phone calls, No pm's, & No multiple emails- We are all volunteers and promise to get back to you within a timely fashion! 
 
Lending A Helping Paw Dog Rescue; previously known as the PRO-PET-OTIC Foundation, is a 100% Foster-Based Rescue that is ran by all Volunteers. Which means that we are not a shelter & each animal is in an actual home with a foster family. We kindly ask that you put any questions within the email & our team of Volunteers will get back to you. With the overwhelming amount of emails please be patient with our 100% volunteer family and we will get back to you. The application MUST BE filled out, a Vet Check MUST BE completed by our team, as well as a phone interview before we do a 'Meet N Greet.'
 
Vet Checks:
When adopting through our rescue, we 'ALWAYS' do a vet check on each applicant's pets that they have owned over the past 10 years. Please make sure to call your vet to grant them permission to release this information to our rescue. That being said, all of the animals in each applicant's home must be UTD on all of their vaccines (DHLPP & Rabies), an UTD Heartworm Test, & currently on both Flea & Tick, as well as Heartworm Prevention. So please make sure that when you are applying that all of your current animals go to the vet that is listed.
 
How To Apply:
If you're interested in adopting one of our available dogs:
1. Email LendingaHelpingPaw313@gmail.com with the dogs name as the subject when you ask for the adoption application.
2. Once you have completed the application, please print it out, fill it out, scan it, & then email it back to LendingAHelpingPaw313@gmail.com. If you do not have a scanner, please take a picture with your phone and we kindly ask that you sent all attachments into one email.
3. Please make sure to call your vet to grant our organization permission to do a vet check on your current pet.
4. If you are interested in more than one dog, please list your top 3 choices on the completed application.
5. Please be honest & truthful on your application. We always do a vet Check. We always do a home visit. And we always have both the prospective families & dogs best interest at heart!

Thank you in advance for all of your love & support,
The Lending A Helping Paw Dog Rescue Family

animal.description: Poor Raisin. He'd been taken to the shelter by his owner because he was diagnosed with diabetes. Unfortunately, instead of giving him care, his owner elected to relinquish him. Probably better for Raisin though, since his owner was keeping him outdoors due to incontinence and only feeding him cat food. Raisin came to us extremely underweight and malnourished, but with a tail that shook with delight. It's almost as if he knew he was going to be in the best care; next to a loving forever home. In addition to being diabetic, Raisin is also sight impaired due to cataracts in both eyes. But, like all Pugs with compromised eyes, he mapped out his new digs in no time. This precious doll is sweet and loving! Once he gets to know you, he'll oftentimes follow you around. He enjoys playing with toys and being around other dogs. He's also an awesome walker on leash - despite not seeing much. Don't let his diabetes deter you from adopting this special and loyal friend. He's very good about taking his injections and has come to expected them the two times per day we administer them. Please consider handsome Raisin as your next forever family member. We're sure you won't be disappointed!

ADOPTION REQUIREMENTS & PROCEDURES
Mutt Match L.A. does not adopt out of state nor do we adopt on a first come first serve basis but rather to the home that is best suited for each particular dog and breed. An application, home check, contract and adoption fee are required for all adoptions. All dogs will be, or required to be, spayed/neutered, current on vaccinations and microchipped before adoption. Most of our dogs are from local LA area shelters, we generally have no prior history for them.
Adoption fees vary between $400 - $500 for puppies 8 weeks - 5 years, $350 6 - 9 years and $300 for dogs over 9 years. Adoption fee covers spay/neuter, vaccinations, microchip a wellness check, any additional medical expenses necessary and of course the all the love and daily care we take with each dog before they are adopted.
We believe a well behaved dog is a happy dog and companion. Therefore, we require at least one session with one of our recommended behaviorists for a reduced fee which is not included in the adoption fee.
We are a busy fully functioning rescue and facility, unfortunately, we do not take requests for more photos and/or video. The photos you currently see are what we currently have and are updated as we recevie new photos. For additional information or questions, please email us at info@muttmatchla.org. To submit an application, please visit us at www.muttmatchla.org. Mutt Match L.A. is an all volunteer rescue, please allow at least 48 hours for a returned response of all inquires.
Thank you! We look forward to hearing from you soon.

animal.description: Are you looking for a handsome fellow to join you on your adventures? Meet Bones, a sweet lab-shepherd mix. Bones came to us from a rescuer in Mexico, where he did not see much of the world. Although he is an easy-going guy in his foster home, he is still shy around new people and unsure of the world outside, like big noises and new places. When he's home, he likes to cuddle with his foster, and play with his canine foster siblings. He is crate trained and loads up easily, with no anxiety or accidents. He likes a good car ride, although sometimes he gets nervous when he reaches the destination if it's not familiar. He will need a family who will be willing to work with him and show him around so he gets used to new places and people. His foster mom reports that he has a ton of potential! He's very lovable and easy to have at home. Because Bones seems to thrive with the company of other dogs, we would like him to go to a home with an existing confident dog. Bones' new home should also be quiet, with a back yard so he can play, relax, and enjoy some quiet time. He would not do well in an apartment situation. Bones is a great size at around 50 pounds, and at 1 year old, he has a lifetime of love and fun to share with his new family. If you are looking for a diamond in the ruff!!, Bones might be your guy. To meet Bones, please fill out an adoption application on the TRD website and an adoption coordinator will be in touch.http://therescueddog.org/dog-adoption-application/

She would do best as the only dog in the house and enjoys the company of older kids. She likes to take very short walks, about 1-2x a week, isn't too interested in dog toys, and likes to sleep in bed, like a person. Miss Ma'am Yuki's ideal home would be quieter, with owners home more often than not, even if this were 'pre-Covid' . If she needs to be kenneled for any short period of time-an Impact Crate is strongly recommended by her foster family. Miss Ma'am Yuki really could best be described as part human, and it doesn't get much better than that! If she sounds like the perfect match for you-contact DPA to set up a meet and greet! All Dallas Pets Alive adoptable pets are spayed or neutered, microchipped, and up to date on vaccines upon adoption. The standard minimum donation for dogs over six months to seven years is $200, puppies under six months is $250, dogs eight years and over are $100 unless specified otherwise. You can view all the adoptable pets and fill out an adoption application online on our website at http://dallaspetsalive.org/adopt/adoptable-dogs/ For more information, you can email adopt@dallaspetsalive.org

Scooby loves loves loves to swim and play ball. Do you need company in your pool? He loves to lay on the float with you as well. This boy is so special but does have some issues that require a special home. His prey drive issues prevent him from living in a home with cats, small dogs or small children.

Scooby had a rough start and missed some socialization skills as a pup. He has not had a stable home until his foster parents fell in love and adopted him. Unfortunately as he settled in, some prey instincts started showing up and for the safety of their other animals (little dogs and cats) they have to rehome him. They will assist with anything he needs and help the transition as much as possible. He is neutered, up to date on all vetting, crate trained, NOT at all destructive and loves to snuggle on the couch with you
Please visit our site at http://zoosrezcue.org for more information on how to adopt. Prior to inquiring about our animals, we highly encourage you to fill out an application so that we can better assist you. Please find our application either from our website or at https://service.sheltermanager.com/asmservice?account=jh2202&method=online_form_html&formid=38

We welcome you to join our Facebook family, so check us out and like us at https://facebook.com/zoosrezcue

animal.description:
** NOTE - LADY HAS REC'D MANY APPLICATIONS AND A FAMILY IS SPEAKING WITH THE FOSTER NOW IN REGARDS TO ADOPTION. WE APOLOGIZE IF WE DIDN'T GET TO YOU. WE ARE HAVING TROUBLE REPLYING TO PETFINDER INQUIRIES. IF THE POSSIBLE ADOPTERS SPEAKING TO THE FOSTER DO NOT WORK OUT, WE WILL CONTINUE THROUGH THE APPLICATIONS. THANK YOU FOR YOUR PATIENCE! **

Name:  Lady
Gender: Female (spayed)
Age: 6-7 years

Dogs: NO. 
Cats: Yes (dog savvy cats, please)
Kids: Yes (dog savvy kids, please)

Lady would love to find a family where she can be your Very Good Girl! She loves her people and is happiest when she's hanging out with her humans. A snuggle on the couch, a snooze in the bed, helping you do your yardwork - she would like to be part of it all. Someone home part days, or someone who works from home would be ideal for her. 

She is NOT a fan of other dogs and cannot live with another dog.  She will not be a candidate for doggie park visits and will not do well in a home that has family or friends who visit with their dogs.  If you are looking for a loyal, loving, happy companion who wants to be your One and Only, Lady is your girl!

Lady loves to be brushed, making coat maintenance a dream for a Collie person. She's a very affectionate girl who looks at grooming as more time for you to pay attention to her!  Like many Collies, she can be a barker when excited, playing, alerting. Someone used to Collies will understand this and not be too bothered by it.

Lady is good with children and will be fine with kids aged 10+. As always with children, it is your responsibility to ensure your kids know the "doggie rules" especially with new adoptions, so time and space is given for your new furry family member to settle in.

She currently lives with cats and for the most part ignores them. She occasionally is more interested, she might chase a cat who runs from her all the time. A dog savvy cat would be fine with Lady.

Leashed walks are right up Lady's ally. She is excellent on-leash but know that other dogs are not her thing, so if you live in a very dog-centric neighbourhood, more time playing in the yard might work best for her.

Lady is a lovely little girl who will thrive in a home where she is the apple of your eye. 

If you feel Lady is a good fit for your family/home, please take the time to fully read our adoption process found here: http://www.collierescuenetwork.com/adoptionprocess.html.  Please then fill out the online adoption application found here: https://form.jotform.com/80865656855271

Can you help me be HOME for the Holidays? This is going to be my first Christmas, and I really want to celebrate with my very own family! 

My name is Tater Tot, but my friends call me Dak. I’m about 10 months old, and I just graduated from the PAWS program. I’m a good boy, I learned all of the good things there, and I love to play. I would love a home with another playful dog.

India is full of love! She loves her favorite humans, and most of all, adventuring in the great outdoors, and nothing lifts a day from good to great like ending it with an India-led ramble through the park. If you have a big heart and a taste for adventure, why not take a vacation to a whole new world of light and love without ever leaving home? Ask us about welcoming India into your life today!

animal.description: Hilda is looking for a home with Helga. We're not sure if they're mother/daughter, sisters, or just plain ol' BFFs, but they definitely belong together. Hilda is the more nervous of the two. On her own, it takes a lot more time to win her over. With her bud Helga around, though, she's a lot more brave. She'll approach cautiously to sniff you, and you'll know you're in when she sticks around for neck scratches. Pretty soon, she'll not only let you pet her, but she'll shove her nose under your hand for more when you stop! Together with Helga, Hilda is a lot more confident and playful. They chase each other and explore everything as a pair, always making sure the other is near by. Once you gain their trust, they even try to fit on your lap at the same time. Hilda and Helga are looking for a quiet but active family. They will need to be the only dogs and with children over 12. They need a house with a fenced yard (preferably a privacy fence), so no apartment life for this duo. Do you have space in your home and your heart for two bashful ladies? Come meet Hilda and Helga! Helga and Hilda are Diamond Dogs and will be shown by appointment only. Diamond Dogs are dogs that are currently receiving special training from staff and volunteers through our behavior modification program. If you are interested in learning more about this animal, please fill out an application by clicking here . Be sure to include Helga and Hilda when filling out the survey. After reviewing your application, we will only be reaching out to you if the animal is a good fit for your home.

animal.description:
Hi, I'm Jimmy.  I am an approximately 6 year old, neutered male.  When I was rescued from Animal Control, I had heartworm; but I have gone thru heartworm treatment now and am ready to find my forever home.  The Rescue says I’m like a guy that just came out of a bad relationship...I take some time to warm up to people I don't know, but once I am comfortable with you and trust you, I love to give kisses.  Right now, any sudden movements startle me, so I'm not sure I'm ready for children yet.  My favorite toy is my Kong.  No crate...just need a room with a view; I love to watch the world go by. Car rides...sometimes I'm a backseat driver, although I am working on getting better.  I walk great on a leash (except when a squirrel or rabbit shows up).

I'm not a guy for a first time pup owner.  I've been around the block and am pretty smart; someone who has had or is experienced with terriers would be great!  I'm a low key kind of guy; I can get wild for five minutes and then I'm good the rest of the day.  Also, if you leave ANY food out, I will FIND it, and I will EAT it!  Oh, I gained a little weight while I was on bed rest during the heartworm treatment. I am aiming to lose seven pounds (I weigh 42 pounds currently....but more of me to love)!  I'm loyal and will alert you of stranger danger or squirrels when we take a walk.  So let’s get our life together started!

animal.description:
Meet Wilson! Wilson is 2 years old and 62 pounds. He is a standard tri color Purebred Aussie. He is UTD on everything. Heartworm/tick disease negative and current on prevention. 

Wilson came into rescue with some high value resource guarding behaviors and because of his guarding behaviors Wilson is NOT for a first time dog owner and his adopter will be required to continue his training and be comfortable with his current training methodology, as other methodologies have not been successful.  His perfect person will need to be 100% familiar with dog behavior and body language.  He is Potty/house trained. Sleeps well at night in the bedroom. He loves to be in the bed, on the sofa or in a dog bed. Does well in 6 foot fenced yard. Doesn't try to jump or dig under fence to escape. Goes into kennel when you say "in". He stays in the kennel while no one is home and does okay. He does bark a lot while in the kennel because he isn't a fan of being in it and being alone. He does have separation anxiety. He hates being alone. He's very velcro and always craves attention.

He loves attention, scratches and cuddles. Does great with happy, social, friendly dogs. Plays with dogs well. He's fine with and respects small senior dogs. He is iffy with dominant/alpha dogs. Sometimes shows teeth and growls at dogs who are dominant/alpha. I'd say he needs a home with another friendly/social dog, not a dog that's dominant/alpha. Not cat or child tested but with past issues no children or cats!  Wilson knows a ton of commands and needs to be kept active and mentally stimulated.  Wilson has done some beginner agility and loves it, also he would do great at Rally, obedience, and more! Wilson has never met a stranger! He is fostered in Auburn GA and will need to be adopted local to continue with his training.

If you think this handsome dude is the right fit for you, please fill out our application:

https://www.australianshepherdsfurever.org/adoption-application

All adoption fees are used for future rescue efforts.

animal.description:
Bella was found as a stray in NYC and brought to the NYCACC (New York City Animal Care Centers - The Municipal City Shelter) in July.  She then was placed on the Euthanasia List due to space issues at the shelter.

We were able to save her as a very generous woman stepped up to save her life.

Bella has had a hard life.  It's obvious from the burn wounds she suffered that have now healed.  They (the Veterinarians) do not know the nature of the burns, but they best guessed them to be chemical in nature.

Age:  Approx. 3
Weight:  Approx 60
Vaccinated:  Yes
Spayed
Housetrained:  Bella is house trained.  She is pretty much on a schedule where she goes out every 3-4 hours.  If she can’t wait in between she will sit at the door to bark to let you know she needs to go out.  

Bella is also trained for pee pads because I didn’t really like to take her out in the hot summer while her wound was healing and the sun was scorching. She does not currently use pads and does prefer to be outdoors to do her business.
Good on leash:  
Kids:  14+
Strangers:  Yes
Dogs:  Yes

She does well with dogs.  She wants to constantly rough house but because of her open skin needs boundaries to protect her as she doesn’t have any fur on her back.  She even does well with little dogs and lets them boss her around.  She doesn’t let the big dogs boss her around tho.    

Bella would do best in a home with older kids.  She likes to throw her weight around and thinks she is a tiny lap dog. While she does get along with other dogs she would also do best as the only dog for now as she loves to get all the attention.  Bella likes to rough play with other dogs but due to her lacking fur on her back she needs to be extra careful not to scratch her skin on her back.  We hope her fur will grow back but we can not be sure if it will at this time.  

Bella needs a home with a big yard and someone who likes to take several walks.  She is full of energy constantly.  If she doesn’t have the ability to walk off her energy she needs lots and lots of toys for stimulation.  She loves her bones, ropes, and really loves to play tug of war with any toy she gets her hands on.  She will want you to play with her all day and sometimes she demands it which is why she needs lots of exercise maybe Someone who likes to hike.  Bella was severely burned and has no fur on her back and again we aren’t sure if it will grow back at this time.  If her fur does not grow back Bella will constantly need to have coats in the winter and sunblock in the summertime.  She also does best wearing small T-shirts to help keep her warm inside and even to protect her from the sun.  She wears a kids size 14/16 and looks great in pink.

Bella knows basic commands like sit and stay using words and hand signals.  She is very treat motivated and we are working on her giving paw.  Bella also likes to sleep in the bed snuggled up close.  Bella knows when she is cold and when she wants to get under the covers she will tell you.  If you have a big home with a big yard and like to exercise Bella would love to share a bed with you.  Bella doesn’t care for doggy beds she just chews them to shreds so she does best with a blanket to snuggle but really prefers to sit and lay anywhere her human does.

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.Nutmeg is a super sweet 2 year old lab mix. She recently had a litter of adorable pups but now that nursing is done and they are on their way home she's ready to find her forever too. She is a STRONG girl and has alot of energy so an active family /owner is ideal. We're also working on boundaries and listening ears

Nutmeg loves to run and play but if you sit down it is officially snuggle time and that better include some belly rubs before she rolls off the couch! She is partially house trained but will need a little more help from her forever family. She loves her human and doggy siblings in foster care but plays too rough with cats to live with them.

Our first step is an application which can be filled out at: www.cvrrescue.org

The adoption fee for this dog is $175.00 which helps to cover a portion of the care provided, including: spay/neuter, microchip, heartworm testing, deworming, age appropriate vaccinations: DHLP/P, Bordetella, Rabies, and any medical care received while with CVRR. All animals are on flea/tick and parasite prevention for the duration of foster care.

CVRR is a nonprofit organization, we have no paid staff. Applications are reviewed and processed by our volunteers. Please be patient and understand that it takes an average of 7-14 days to process the applications including reference checks and follow-up questions. You can expedite the process by providing phone and email info for all your references.

Once your application is approved, we will schedule a meet-and-greet to see if the dog picks you too. If it seems the adoption will be a good match for all, there is an adoption fee and an adoption contract to be signed. The adoption fee helps to cover a portion of the care provided to the animals. By the time of adoption all dogs are spayed/neutered, microchipped, and up to date on vetting.

CVRR is a NO KILL rescue organization and we have a LIFETIME COMMITMENT to all of our animals. If for any reason the adoption does not work out the animal is to be returned to CVRR. We will re-evaluate and choose a new home based on the best fit for that particular animal.

animal.description:
BACKSTORY:
Sometimes people don’t include arrangements in their wills, or other documents, for the care of their pet in the event they pass away. And unfortunately, this was the very case. A 10+ year old boy with stunning good looks landed at an area animal control when his owner passed away and there wasn’t any other family to take him in. Life doesn’t look like it’s been easy for him...he’s extremely underweight, there were pressure sores and missing fur, he’s not too stable on his legs, and he’s got a mouth full of rotten & broken teeth. Being stuck in a kennel at animal control is no place for a super senior...they should be lounging on furniture, getting all the pets possible, and surrounded by unconditional love. Well, we were able to make that happen thanks to a selfless foster who has a soft spot like us, for elderly pups. Bernie is looking for a loving home to nap in for the rest of his days.

EDUCATION:
* Sit
* House trained
* Lower energy
* Superstar on leash
* Doesn't need to be crated
 
ACTIVITIES THIS CUTIE ENJOYS: 
* Treats: not picky except he won't eat carrots
* Food: his foster says sausage biscuits?!
* Toys: a blue nylabone and a white bear he sleeps with
* Walks: superstar
* Enjoys affection
* Loves to sleep
* Snuggling
* Belly scratches
* Wagging his tail all day long
 
SKILLS:
* Dogs: friendly
* Kids: unknown
* People: friendly
* Cats: unknown

CHALLENGES:
* Needs a home with little to no stairs
* Isn't a fan of the healthy food he's supposed to be eating

animal.description:
Please help us find Marlo the perfect home....  This is a courtesy post, Marlo is being placed privately, not by the shelter.  

If you are experienced with working dogs and would like to find out more about adopting Marlo please email hopeformarlo@gmail.com   Or visit his facebook page at (cut and paste to your browser):  https://www.facebook.com/Hope-For-Marlo-102251291791995/?view_public_for=102251291791995

Marlo is a very special boy indeed.  We can say with certainty that he isn't the dog for everyone.  In fact, most people wouldn't know how to channel his high drive personality.  But for the right person who understands the trait, Marlo would be the perfect fit!  

You see a high drive dog needs a job to do.  They have a focused intensity, a desire to work, that makes them overcome all obstacles in pursuit of the goal.  A high drive dog needs plenty of mental and physical stimulation to prevent boredom and to expend their physical energy.  

This is where the problem lies.  With Marlo in a kennel, he has become frustrated and deeply bored.  He has begun to act out, most notably by being inappropriately mouthy.  With lack of regular stimulation, he gets super worked up when even the smallest amount of stimulation is introduced.  

Marlo is very smart and does follow basic commands.  We are certain that he would excel with an experienced owner that can provide the training, stimulation and consistency needed for a high drive dog.  

A trainer recently assessed Marlo and felt he was just a very smart but frustrated dog who would blossom with the right owner.  A group of dedicated volunteers have been working with him each day and he is doing amazing.  But he needs a home with experience training and working with young, bright and active dog.

We are committed to trying to find the best permanent placement  for the boy we have all come to love.  If you would like more information please send us an email at hopeformarlo@gmail.com   Do not contact the shelter as he is not available for adoption through them.  This is simply a courtesy post.

animal.description:
Marshall is a male Pit Bull mix who was born around September 2018 and weighs 45 pounds.

He was picked up as a stray in the county and was emaciated and malnourished upon arrival. He weighed just 35 pounds. Thankfully, after recovering in our care he is back to a healthier weight, and he's ready to go to his forever home! Marshall would be a great walking companion - he LOVES going on walks!

The adoption fee for Marshall is $175. This includes spay/neuter, rabies, distemper, bordatella, flea treatment, worming, testing for heartworms and treatment, and microchiping.

If you are interested in meeting Marshall, please visit the shelter at 22407 Bus Hwy 151 on the outskirts of Monticello during normal business hours which are Tuesday thru Saturday, noon to 6:30pm. If you have any further questions, you can call 319-975-8283.

BREED DISCLAIMER: Many dogs come to us as strays and therefore, we are unsure of their breed. We may actually list a pure bred as a mix because we truly do not know their origins or background and we often must guess at their breed.

animal.description:
Hi. My name is Yoshi. I am a good looking girl with brindle markings and beautiful blue eyes.  I weigh 41 pounds and my veterinarian thinks I may be a shepherd mix.  At about two years old, I am still a young girl.

 I am energetic and I love to play, run and go on brisk walks. I think I would like to go hiking, but I have ever had the opportunity.   I like to play with other dogs, but my foster siblings are getting up in years and so they are not very interested in playing.

 My foster mom says that I can be vocal when I want something. She has taught me some simple commands such as "sit" and "give me your hand" . I can also do a high 5, but I only do that when I feel in the mood.

 My first family put me in a crate a lot because they thought I had too much energy.  Now I tend to get really excited when I finally get to go out and run around. I know I can be calmer when I get to live somewhere where I don't have to be crated so much, but it might take a little bit of time and work for me to learn more polite manners.

I am spayed, vaccinated and up to date on vaccines.

animal.description:
Hello, my name is Ziggy and I am looking for a Christmas miracle. All I want for Christmas is a family to call my own.  I used to live on the streets in Houston and had a really hard time and didn't like being alone. I enjoy spending time with people and snuggling up on the couch. I especially like to lay in front of a warm fire when I can. It helps me forget about my cold, lonely days. I can be active but enjoy chilling and watching movies as well. I like kids but I get really excited when they are running around and having fun.  It makes me sad when I knock them down but I never mean to hurt anyone. So, I would prefer the bigger ones!  One of my favorite things is to play with other dogs but sometimes they just don't understand me, and it causes problems.  I much prefer the ladies, they get me! My foster parents have other dogs and I was especially bonded to my friend Lilly that passed a few weeks ago.  She loved snuggling with me, and I have been really sad and missing her a lot.  I am a really sweet boy and I just want a family to love me! So, if you think you can be the home for me, please make my Christmas wishes come true! I have been waiting for you my whole life!

animal.description: Meet Goofy!  Goofy is a ~11 month old terrier mix.  His story is sad... he was found abandoned in a house when he was only a 4 month old puppy... Despite a tough beginning, this boy is as happy as can be!  Did I also say smart?  Wicked smart!  He knows all the basics, down, sit, crawl, shake, stay, come... he is a smarty pants!  Goofy's potential is infinite!  He would make a great Canine Good Citizen!  Maybe even an agility guy or Therapy Dog - he could do just about anything as long as he has a family that could just give him a chance!  Goofy LOVES balls and toys of any kind... but we think Nyla or Nylon type would live up to his expectations.  Goofy is fine with other dogs - and loves to romp in the yard with them.  Cats?  We just don't know yet.  Since Goofy is still working on his manners with new people (he is typically so excited he jumps up...) teenage children would be best for him.

You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.Princess here,
I am looking for a best friend to adopt me or someone to foster me. For fostering, vetting and food would be paid for by the rescue.I am a very loving, easy girl. I had an owner I got away from, which was probably best. I am 9 years old and apx 40 pounds. I was covered in fleas with hair loss and my eyes were all gooped up. My back end is arthritic, so I am afraid I don't have much time left. Hopefully, a 2-3years.My owners could not keep up with my vetting. We are living in tough times for people and pets. I have been treated for the fleas and my eyes are good now. I am totally vetted and I have a comfy human bed to sleep on. I feel like a queen, instead of a princess now. I need to be the only dog in the home. I can be a little snarky with certain dogs and will not be nice to them. I am very loyal to my people. I love to be petted and will give a gentle kiss for that. I was raised around children, so I am fine with older, considerate children. I also lived with cats. I would be a great calm, companion to you. I am low maintenance. I feel like a new girl now. I am on pain meds for the hip arthritis(apx $15 a month) and fish oil for my skin and glucosamine for my joints. Like some of us older women, I am incontinent at night. The rescue will pay for my proin, which controls that perfectly. I sure would like my own person to sit next to. I could comfort them and they could pet me. That would be my heart's delight.If you would like to be my new best friend, please fill an ap out below.

animal.description:
Get ready for the explosion of personality that is Paxton! This big, exuberant guy has a real zest for life and lots of opinions. He loves, loves, loves to play with toys and will certainly let you know if you're moving too slowly with his favorite thing - the tennis ball! Paxton has clearly had some training as he already seems to know sit, down, paw and speak. Paxton is big and strong and would do best with someone who doesn't mind a lot of enthusiastic dog in their life. He is hilarious, friendly and super playful and should be a lot of fun for his future active family. We estimate Paxton to be around 4 years old and he weighs 83 lbs. 

Visit www.tinyurl.com/meetacitydog to meet playful smarty-pants Paxton!
Due to COVID-19, CITY DOGS is currently doing adoptions by APPOINTMENT ONLY. Please visit www.tinyurl.com/meetacitydog to request a meet and greet! 

Questions? Email: citydogs@city.cleveland.oh.us | Call: (216) 664-3476
Visit: 9203 Detroit Avenue Cleveland, OH 44102

Hours:
10 AM - 3 PM Monday, Wednesday, Friday, Saturday, Sunday
10 AM - 6 pm Tuesday & Thursday

Fee: $61 | Includes spay/neuter, shots, microchip, license, 30 days free pet insurance (when registered upon adoption)

The CITY DOGS mission is to increase adoptions from the City Kennel by changing the image of the pit bulls who make up the majority of the kennel population, by preparing all adoptable dogs in the kennel for lives in loving homes and by creating as many opportunities as possible for the public to meet and get to know our dogs for the terrific pets they are meant to be.

Our Adoption Process...
Here's a little about how things work:
All of the CITY DOGS posted for adoption are available for direct adoption from the kennel, unless noted otherwise. You must schedule a meet with a dog in advance - we are not currently accepting walk-ins. Please look online first to see if there are any dogs you think would be a good fit for your home before scheduling a meet. To get the process started, visit www.tinyurl.com/meetacitydog and fill out the form. One of our adoption counselors will get in touch to schedule and confirm your meet! At the kennel, an adoption counselor will introduce you and your family to the adoptable dogs, share information we know about them, and discuss our suggested ways for successfully integrating a new dog into your home. You are welcome to meet multiple dogs. If the dog you adopt is already fixed, he or she may leave with you that day - otherwise, the dog can go home after receiving the spay or neuter surgery.)

About Our Dogs: All available dogs have gone through a behavioral and medical assessment. This assessment is a snapshot of who the dog is at that given time. We cannot make any guarantees with regard to behavior, temperament or health of any City Dog once they are in the home. Most of our dogs are picked up as strays, so we do not know what kind of home environment they were living in (i.e. with kids, other dogs or other cats), nor do we know if most of them are house trained. Everything we know about them is based on volunteer and staff observations. We do have some dogs in foster homes, where they will have more information about how the dog is in a home environment. It is very hard to tell with certainty whether or not a dog will be good with kids, cats or another dog. If you have kids in the home or another dog, we do require that they be present for a meet and greet with the dog you are considering for adoption.

Heath/Vaccinations: Dogs that are adopted directly from the kennel need to go to your personal vet within two weeks of leaving the kennel. All dogs receive their DAPPL, Rabies, and Bordatella vaccines, though you may be required to get follow up boosters. All dogs come microchipped and with a Cuyahoga County license.?

animal.description:
MEET ZANDER!!

You can tell from Zander's picture he is a timid boy. He's almost 2 years old, but appears he might've been a backyard dog. Zander is under socialized and will need an experienced and patient owner who can work on his training and behavior. Upon intake to the shelter Zander was scared and confused, and was seen growling in his kennel when someone got close. After just a couple days he showed some progress with the handler, but is still cautious. When the handler attempted to pet him he quickly turned his head around and his lip curled. He's starting to understand that the handlers will not hurt him, but needs someone to continue showing him that so he can enjoy the rest of his life not in fear! He's already wagging his tail when the handler comes to his kennel, and does bump the handler in the yard, but isn't seeking out attention beyond that yet. He hasn't been interested in the other dogs in the yard. There haven't been any issues, but he hasn't shown interest in them either. If you currently have dogs a meet and greet will be strongly recommended. Because of his timidness and under socialization a home with no children is recommended.

If you are interested in Zander, please visit our website for our application www.underdogaz.com

To adopt, complete our online adoption application and an Adoption Counselor will contact you within 48-hours to schedule your adoption appointment. Adoptions for any pets in foster will be completed offsite at our PetSmart Claiborne location on a case by case basis. The safety of our foster parents and community is of utmost importance to us and it will be at the foster's discretion if they'd like to meet at this time. Thank you for choosing adoption!

My name is Queenie but I promise I won't brag about it! I have a heart full of gold and can't wait to find my forever home. I love to spend time in the yard playing to get my energy out and am always excited to go on walks as well. Fill out an application and PUT MY NAME ON IT so we can meet and hang out! I am located at the Plaquemines campus.



To inquire about an adoptable animal from the Louisiana SPCA, please call 504.368.5191, ext. 150 to speak with an adoption counselor.
To see more adoptable animals from the Louisiana SPCA, please go to http://la-spca.org/adopt.



The petfinder.com system requires that we choose a predominant breed or breed mix for our dogs. Visual breed identification in dogs is unreliable so for most of the dogs we are only guessing at predominant breed or breed mix. We get to know each dog as an individual and will do our best to describe each of our dogs based on personality, not by breed label.

animal.description:
Marshall is his given name but we call him Loaf. Our home won't be the same without this amazing old man, but his adopters are in for a treat!!! He's loving and friendly with every creature he meets. He's gentle and caring. He wants nothing more than to relax and enjoy his people. He is overweight with several fat lumps, a heart murmur and arthritic but that doesn't dampen his spirits. This guy may have the body of an old man but his soul is as youthful as ever. He enjoys playing but can only do short bursts. He loves to walk, were only up to about a mile give or take depending on the day. He loves car rides and sunshine. He loves a fenced yard but can also wander next to you leashed or free. This lovable Loaf, will require ongoing anti-inflammatory meds and will need to have daily bursts of exercise, nothing to strenuous - tug of war, throw a toy short distance, chase around the ottoman. He doesn't like to lay directly on the ground but sometimes can't jump, so we have several pillows and low beds for him to choose. He sleeps in a crate at night ( I removed the door) so he has a choice. He has not shown any signs of aggression or territorial behavior. He goes outside regularly and has only had one accident in the house. Do you have a retirement home for Marshall?

ADOPT MARSHALL!!!! www.LuckyPupRescueSC.com The adoption fee is $250 and we require a vet check and home visit (virtual). Marshall is neutered, chipped current on vaccines and been heartworm tested and is on monthly prevention.

animal.description: My name is PRINCESS and I'm a darling 10yr F White/Gray/Brown Shih Tzu. I'm 11 lbs of PURE SUGAR & SPICE. I was rescued from a family that surrendered me due to NO TIME. It's ok because they weren't really giving me the attention I needed and I'm ready for someone who can devote alot more TLC to me. I'm a sweet girl but I'm very guarded when I first meet you so you have to go slow...If you go too fast and try to pet me too quickly I will be snarky and snap at you... so I'm NOT GOOD with young children. Older kids ages 12 yrs+ is best. I was rescued along with another small dog and we had a love/hate relationship... the other dog would go after me and that is probably why I'm BLIND in ONE EYE. I hold no grudges and am fine with other dogs in passing...but I think I would be happiest as A SOLO DOG so I can get all the attention. I need someone who is experienced with dogs that can be "snarky" and someone that is going to go slow and be patient  & compassionate with me to earn my trust and not be offended if I snap at them for going to fast. If that's you... please send an email to: INFO@TAILSOFLOVERESCUE.ORG for an application.

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.Available Soon!Rosie is a 12 pound, 15 year old Chihuahua mix. Rosie is the definition of cute companion pup! Everyone who meets her loves her. She loves kids and being around groups of people, especially when everyone is petting her. She walks very well on the leash and will keep up during short walks. After walks she will usually want to eat a little food, drink some water, and take a nap. When she sleeps, she makes cute little snoring noises. Rosie has an ADORABLY CUTE, granny howl and will use it if she's lonely/looking for you. For the most part, she sleeps and keeps to herself. She will eat a breakfast AND dinner and has a healthy appetite, but she typically sleeps through breakfast. She may eat a bit too quickly, but a slow feed insert slows her down enough to enjoy her food. She prefers wet and dry food mixed together, and will refuse dry food by itself.

When it's warm outside, she prefers to be outdoors soaking up the sun. When it's colder, Rosie loves to lounge around indoors and when she does go outside she enjoys wearing a warm jacket. She is pee-pad trained, but because she cannot see well, it is important to keep things around her in as consistent a place as possible, otherwise she becomes a little confused. Rosie LOVES her bed. It is her safe place and her happy place. She will wander off of it a little bit and will say "hello" to you, then make her way back to her place. Rosie also LOVES blankets. One of her most endearing qualities is how she can get herself tucked in underneath a blanket. Every now and then, she will howl because her blanket needs resetting. If you put the blanket on top of her, she will spin around and lay back down. At night, keeping her contained with her pee pads ensures that she can do her business and stay safe.

Because she doesn't see well, new people can introduce themselves by allowing Rosie to sniff their hand before they pet her. She is also startled by fast moving shadows. Car rides can be challenging, so she does best if she is crated and covered when in the car.

Rosie requires little grooming and has learned to stay in the tub when she's getting bathed. She needs to be dried with a hairdryer and prefers low-heat settings. It's also important to clean all areas of her body to prevent skin infections.

Prior to adoption, all dogs are spayed/neutered, tested for heartworm, vaccinated (including rabies, if age appropriate) and microchipped.

Adoption fees for dogs: http://www.svpetproject.org/info/adoption

Stay up-to-date on what our dogs are up to by following us on Facebook!

https://www.facebook.com/svpetproject

animal.description: Meet Tonka! Tonka has been in a foster home while going through heartworm treatment. He is now heartworm free. This is the bio from his foster: Bull in a china shop is apt for Tonka. He has no personal space & apparently doesn't believe anyone else does! This goes for playing & resting. He's a huge cuddler with people & dogs (he hasn't had a chance with cats). He needs someone who agrees with the idea of a dog sleeping on their bed. He doesn't always stay the whole night, but he does most nights. He takes correction from people and dogs well but that doesn't mean he won't do the corrected behavior again... He is food/treat motivated, so he's learned sit, down, and stay pretty well. He's working on not jumping ("off" command) and not mouthing, which he does when he's excited. He rarely jumps on me except when he has a dog friend over. He loves people and most dogs. I don't think he'd do well with submissive dogs; so adult, confident dogs would work best with him. He's fine with small dogs, as long as they don't act scared. He loves playing outside & entertains himself chasing lizards and playing with toys. He likes to counter-surf, and since he does that when I'm not home, I have rearranged things. The longer I have him, the less of that he seems to do. He's laidback, no separation anxiety. He will be good with kids 9 or so and older. He barks appropriately, not excessively. He likes riding in the car.

animal.description:
Meet Roscoe!

Foster or Adopt Roscoe!

Roscoe is a 7-year-old Pit Mix who weigh approximately 60 lbs. Roscoe is a special boy who is searching for a foster home or a forever home!

Roscoe is really a sweet, playful boy who loves people. He loves to run and fetch a rope toy and zoom back and forth with it. He loves to go for walks and is good on a leash and harness, although he can pull some at first. He also likes to ride in the car. He loves his crate and is a very secure in it. Roscoe is a bit of a Houdini when it comes to escaping fences so he will need a home with a secure back yard.
Roscoe is heartworm positive and will need to undergo treatment which is why he is in urgent need of a foster home. He will need to stay calm during his treatment so a quiet and calm environment would be ideal. Due to past behavioral issues Roscoe will need to go into a home with no other animals or a home with experienced fosters/dog owners who will be able to keep him separate from other pets. 


To adopt or foster Roscoe follow the link below. 
www.bullluvablepaws.org/adopt

animal.description:
Bernard, aka Bernie, is a 14 year old poodle mix. He was rescued from a shelter in July and had a number of health issues that needed to be addressed. He is doing so much better but he still has a chronic cough that the vets have not been able to resolve. 
It's clear that Bernie had a loving home for most of his life because he is sooo sweet and loves everyone he meets. He loves to cuddle in your lap, and will bury his head under your hand to let you know he needs a some loving. He naps for most of the day but is still a very lively little guy and gets very excited when its time to go for a walk. He does most of his business outside, immediately, but cannot be 100% trusted to not have an accident in the house so I keep a belly band on him which he does not mind, and its very effective. 
He gets along with other dogs, and likes to play some, but like most dogs can be territorial when they come near his bed or food. He does not seem interested in cats, so could easily share a home with them. He'd love to have a home where someone is home often to love and care for him during his golden years. 

To set up a meet and greet or inquire about a dog, please first fill out an application at https://savinghoperescue.org/contact. It doesn't obligate you, but it is the first step. We don't get to all of the inquiries but respond to all applications. Thank you for choosing to rescue!

animal.description:
This is Magic!

10-year-old Magic was brought into the Humane Society of Imperial Valley as a stray. He had been adopted from there in 2011 and was microchipped, but his microchip led to dead ends, and he wasn't claimed. So we made Magic a Frosted Face on December 7th, and he is every bit the 100-lbs of love that we hoped he would be!

At our vet, Magic's labs showed a bit of anemia, and his x-rays showed significant hip arthritis. We got him started on pain medication and antibiotics for his skin. He also has a terrible pressure sore on his elbow that the antibiotics will help.

Nothing phases this guy, from kids, to rowdy dogs, to cats. He's too busy looking for his next belly rub!

Magic was chosen for a Frosted Fling for the holidays, and he was such a good boy that it was extended! His Fling Fam is helping him lose weight and giving this sweet hunk lots of love and attention. We received a great update from his Fling Mom: "

Big news! Magic saw the vet today and he has lost 6 lbs!

(Now 98 lbs)

He's built up to walking around the whole block (takes 30+ min) and I actually saw him run a few steps this week... chasing a skateboarder!

Magic

still gets along great with all his Fling brothers, and is even trying to "play"... which mostly consists of head butting them while they play bow and jump around and lick his face!

He loves his crate and knows how to go in on command. That's where he eats, but he likes to lounge around in there (door open) before and after meals too.

We have closed him in once and he did great, but he's also great loose in the living room while we're away.

Magic is 100% potty trained and has not had a single accident.

He continues to be a very easy dog who loves napping, cuddles, laying in the sun, eating, being around people (and kids), adventures that involve napping or laying in the sun in a different place (like the park or beach), barking because his brothers are barking, looking deep into your eyes, and just being part of the family.

In summary, he's basically perfect!"

As much as Magic is enjoying his Fling, he would love a forever home of his own. Might it be with you?

Apply to meet Magic here:
www.frostedfacesfoundation.org/apply/

Visit us at Open House: Saturdays & Sundays, 10 am - 1 pm.

Learn more about our programs at www.frostedfacesfoundation.org/family. No adoption fees, and we help with medical costs!

Apply to become a family: www.frostedfacesfoundation.org/apply

Questions: adopt@frostedfacesfoundation.org

Updated 1/31/21 KG

animal.description:
OPERATION HOME FOR THE HOLIDAYS!!
Meet Theo!!! Theo is a beautiful 9 month old Lab mix who is a goofy, high energy boy who would rather play tug than cuddle on the couch. If you're an avid hiker, if you want a jogging buddy with legs that can go miles, Theo might be your dog. He is an avid foodie but has so far remembered to stay off the counter. He loves car rides and other dogs, but would probably be best as an only pet. He can be intense and has no concept of boundaries, so other animals and children will be bowled over. Redirecting him from cats, or getting him to not be so mouthy when roughhousing with other dogs, is probably unrealistic.
Theo is a bit shy at first and does take some time to warm up.  He is always more interested in toys than he is in meeting other humans.  Other dogs though are his favorite.
When he was returned to us he had some anxiety issues and we have worked through most of it with him.  He has come such a long way since we got him.  He is now doing great but will definitely need structure and continued obedience training to reach his full potential.
Theo is crate trained and his kennel helps him calm down. When he's out, he's *on*. Since he has trouble regulating himself, he needs external boundaries. He is also an enthusiastic chewer and I recommend toys that *don't* have stuffing unless you'd like a snow effect for the holidays.
He is good at Sit and Down, even if he won't hold them long. He tends to pull on the leash but gets better once you really get going. He's gotten the idea of "Leave It". 
He might not be a chill dog, but we are looking for someone who can appreciate his exuberance and energy. Experience with Huskies and other go-go-go breeds is recommended.
If interested in adopting please email us at southernpawsrescue@gmail.com for an Application!

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.

Sampson.....this senior boy has had a rough life. The first 4 years of his life were spent living in a crate 24/7. A friend of the family offered to take Sampson in so he didnt have to live like that anymore. After years of having Sampson, this good man lost his home and had no choice but to live in his vehicle. Feeling that Sampson deserved so much more, he reached out for help. He is 12 years young and absolutely LOVES attention! In exchange for your attention he will gift you with a big slobbery kiss! He enjoys going on walks and playing in his water bowl. He is currently being fostered at the Doggie Lodge and the staff there absolutely adore him! He will sometimes have a pee accident overnight in his kennel and he likes to put his blanket in his water bowl after he has overturned it lol. He doesnt seem too interested in toys but that could change once he settles into his new home. In the kennel environment he appears to be dog selective however we do know he has had play dates with a voluteers' dogs and did well, both male and female. Just prior to coming to ODAAT, Sampson who was not neutered at the time, was attacked by another unneutered male dog when a friend brought their female dog over to play. Sampson did not initiate the altercation but did defend himself without causing injuries to the other dog. Sampson IS neutered now. We are willing to entertain a home with another calmer female dog, medium to large in size, who is respectful of space and sharing, however a home where Sampson could be the apple of his adopters eye would also be suitable. He did live with kids ages 3-14 in his prior home, the only issue being that he would take food out of the little ones hands. Due to his age a home with kids 8 and older who are respectful of dogs will be considered. He does great in the car and well on leash. Sampson did exhibit some separation anxiety in the home where he would claw at the door when they left and potty just inside the door. He would do best in a home where someone is home more than they are not, not just during the time of COVID but even after life returns to normal. He did live with cats in his prior home as well and did great. He is your typical laid back boxer just looking for some love in the years he has left and we are devoted to finding him that and more! If you can provide all of the things Sampson needs, please apply at
www.onedogatatime.us

animal.description:
PHOTOS:  Virtually all of our dogs have online PHOTO ALBUMS through SmugMug with LOTS of additional pictures.  Just copy and paste the link below into your browser (or simply type it in) and then search for the dog's "gallery" by name

          http://adoptasleddog.smugmug.com

VIDEOS:  In addition to photo albums, almost every dog has a video which will give you a much better "feel" for his or her personality.  NOTE:  In the new Petfinder format, it has become quite a bit more difficult to find and to play videos.  Please PAGE THROUGH the photos, looking for a photo overlaid in the center with a "play" arrow inside a circle.  This icon is white, so it can be difficult to see. 
 In many (most) cases, the video is the last photo displayed as you page through.  Just click on that photo and it will play.  Please make sure you CHECK ON THE PETFINDER VIDEO ICON, above, to see a video of this wonderful dog!  Our videos will include, at a minimum, whatever info we had on the dog upon (or shortly after) his/her arrival into our program.  There will sometimes be video updates as well.  And in every case, our Adoptions Coordinator can be emailed at ADOPTASLEDDOG@AOL.COM to answer questions and provide the most current information we have on the dog.  

NOTES:  Please see video or contact our Adoptions Coordinator at ADOPTASLEDDOG@AOL.COM.

ADOPTION DONATION:  $250  Before adoption, all Northern Lights dogs (regardless of whether Petfinder's symbols appear) are spayed or neutered, microchipped, heartworm negative, fully vaccinated and tested/treated for known parasites.
 
WHAT TO DO IF YOU WANT TO ADOPT THIS DOG:  Email us at ADOPTASLEDDOG@AOL.COM to request an application and get started.  WE DO NOT HAVE AN ONLINE APPLICATION - you will have to request one via email.  We will review your application to determine if there is a good fit between you and/or your family and this dog.  We may suggest another dog or dog(s) if we can offer a better fit in terms of lifestyle, experience, other pets, etc.  A vet check, reference checks, and a home visit will be conducted before an adoption can be considered for approval.  
 
NORTHERN LIGHTS DOES NOT HAVE A PHYSICAL SHELTER.  We are a nonprofit rescue organization comprised of individuals who open their private homes to foster dogs in need of a second chance..  When fosters are not available, we often pay to board a dog until space is available.  New fosters and donations to pay for boarding are always desperately needed us.  Email us at KATYLIED2@AOL.COM if you are interested in donating or for information on fostering.
 
FAQ:  For information regarding our organization, as well as adoption policies and practices, please visit our Petfinder Home Page at WWW.NORTHERNLIGHTS.PETFINDER.COM.
 
 
NOTICE:  In the vast majority of cases, the dogs in our program and rescued from shelters, and Northern Lights has no means by which to collect or verify a dog's history.  We work in concert with our veterinarians, and breed and age estimates are based on a combination of professional input and our collective experience.  Our policy with information acquired prior to acceptance and while the dogs are in our care is that of "full disclosure".  It is our goal to ensure the adopter has all available information to ensure the best possible match between the dog and the adopter(s).  If we have identified a behavioral or health condition while the dog is in our care and custody, every effort will be made to correct it prior to adoption, OR the adopter will be made aware of the issue or condition prior to adoption.  Northern Lights' screening process is designed to identify only those adopters who are willing, and have the means, to treat conditions which may occur after adoption, and the adopter will be contractually responsible for doing so. However, Northern Lights' policy is to accept any adopted dog back into the program, at any time, for any reason.

COURTESY POSTING FOR ANIMAL RESCUE ASSISTANCE TEAM TN

Meet Sadie 

I’m a 3 yr old spayed American Staffordshire Terrier (with pretty pale Brindle markings). I am heartworm negative, weigh about 80lbs, and I am up to date on my vaccinations. I was brought into ARATT with my friend Gucci who has been kenneled with for the past three years. My family moved away and couldn’t take us with them; and we were left in unkept conditions. I am kind of a chunky gal, so I need somebody to continue to help me with a healthy diet (even though I love treats). I’m pretty laid-back and can be very shy at first; but I smile at you and will wag my tail once I get to know you (you just have to take it slow at first when meeting me). Once I know you’re my person, I will be a Velcro pup and never leave your side. I need to be adopted into a home without cats (I like to chase them) and without other dogs (unless I can be adopted with my buddy Gucci). If you are looking for more than one dog; Gucci and I are the perfect pair (we will be fine if we are separated too though). I am crate trained and almost house trained with minimal accidents (I'm still learning since I've always lived in an outside kennel). I would do best in a home without children or in a home with older kids because I do jump up and get can get over excited. I'm a fast learner and am very food motivated (as you can see from my plump belly).

"Your love was worth the wait." Obie is a handsome 75 lbs Great Pyrenees male. Obie is very shy when first meeting new people, but once he warms up to you, you are his best friend. He requires time to adjust to any new surroundings.

Obie was born around June 2019 and was one of many puppies rescued when the Great Pyrenees Rescue Society (GPRS) retrieved a litter of puppies dumped in a rural Texas field. Obie has been living at headquarters, waiting to be adopted into his forever home.

Obie would thrive in an all adult family with no other pets. He needs exercise, daily walks or hikes and securely fenced yard to run and play in. Obie needs confident leaders in his family who are familiar with Pyr traits and behavior. If you believe you are the family he has been waiting for, please complete an Adoption Application for Obie.

All dogs and puppies require VISIBLE fencing

Adoption Fee: $300. (Adoption fee includes spay/neuter, heartworm test, rabies, distemper, parvo and health certificate for travel). Adoption applications can be found on our website at

https://www.greatpyreneesrescuesociety.org/

Northwest adopters pay the cost of transport to independent transport service ($200)

ADOPTION, FOSTERING, AND DONATIONS are just some of the ways you can help a rescued dog. We have worked hard to cultivate a large network of volunteers to save this majestic breed. While monetary donations are always much appreciated, you can also help by donating your time as a GPRS foster or volunteer!

animal.description:
COURTESY POSTING FOR ANIMAL RESCUE ASSISTANCE TEAM TN

Meet Gucci

My name is Gucci. I am a neutered 3 yr old American Staffordshire Terrier (perfect blue boy). I’m heartworm negative, weigh about 60lbs, and am up to date on my vaccinations. I have been kenneled with my friend Sadie my whole life. I am now in foster care with ARATT. I am learning what it’s like to actually be a dog and have someone care for me. My foster mom says that I am a fast learner; I just had no one to teach me good manners. I do like to jump and because of my size, I don’t realize my strength. I can get rough and get mouthy at play time, but you can give me a toy to help with that. I would be best in a home with no kids due to my energy and size. I’d love someone I can play tug-of-war with and continue teach me what it’s like to be spoiled. I love splashing in my toddler pool in the summer. I’m doing really well on my crate training so that would make it pretty easy for me to learn how to be house trained. I love to go out and explore new things (I'm a super curious boy); so I will require a fenced in back yard. I do really well on a leash and love to go on walks! I think cats are meant for chasing; so my foster mom says I will need a home without cats. I also would need to go into a home with no other dogs (unless you are interested in adopting Sadie and I together) because I still have a lot to learn and I try to be overly dominant with other dogs. I just need to learn my limits and have someone to help me with that. Sadie and I have known each other for the past three years and have been limited to our kennel together. I know that Ms. Sadie is the boss lady! We would do fine adopted separately, but would also make a wonderful pair if you are interested in the both of us!
animal.name: Courtesy Posting: Gucci

animal.description:
Welcome to the Wonderful World of Rescue Dachshunds. Look around and read their bios. Find a few whose personality seems to fit well. Consider one of our Well Seasoned Seniors who are truly wonderful and have so much to offer. Need help finding the best fit? We'll help with that too. Please fill out an application and let's get you all matched up with a loving new "furever' companion and friend. You'll find the application on the "Available Dogs" page.

NOTE:

Adoptions to Central/South Texas residents only

Standard Adoption Fee Adult Dog: $250 ea. Puppy Adoption Fee: $300 ea. Reduced rates for Seniors dogs (10 and up). Reduced rates for pairs (when adopted together). All adoption fees are subject to sales tax per the State of Texas. DDRTX only adopts in Central/South Texas.

Email: ddrtxinfo@gmail.com Primary Website: www.DDRTX.org
Meet General Button! General came to DDRTX after being found by a good Samaritan.

He weighs in at about 5.5 pounds and his estimated age is about 12 years old. Since coming to rescue he's had some major dental work, leaving him with just 2 teeth! He's been neutered and had a tumor removed. Although the tumor was cancerous, it was not malignant. Now that he is neutered, there is a good chance it will not return.

After all he's been through, he's the happiest, sweetest little guy! He is house trained and crate trained. He will sleep alone but he sure does love to snuggle in the big bed with his foster mom. He does like to take short walks but due to his age, he gets chauffeured around in his stoller.... which he loves!

He may be an older guy, but to know him is to love him! If you are interested in giving this little guy a loving home, submit your application today!

Love dachshunds and not ready to adopt or circumstances won't permit having a dog? How about being a sponsor or making a donation. Every one of our dachshunds receives excellent medical care along with day to day food, love and housing. Being non-profit, we rely on generous individuals like yourselves to help save these fur babies. You can do this specifically for one dog with the sponsor button on their webpage or a general donation on our "How To Help" page. Easy and quick through Pay Pal or your debit/credit card. You generosity is sincerely appreciated by all and is tax deductable. Need other ideas? You'll find tons of them on the How to Help tab. All contributions are tax deductable.

Diamond Dachshund Rescue of Texas is a non-profit 501(c)(3) volunteer organization with focus on rescue and adoption of pure breed Dachshunds. All dogs are fully vetted and housed on private property. Meetings are scheduled upon adoption approval. Thank you for your continued support to the rescue and shelter communities!
Opt to Adopt!

29 Stagebridge Road, Lovingston, VA 22949

IMPORTANT!!! PLEASE READ

Posted animals are physically located at the above address except when indicated with the following notations after the animal's name:

Animal Name (FC=initials) -- indicates the animal is living in Foster Care. To meet the animal, please contact the foster directly when contact information is provided; otherwise call the shelter at 434 263-7722.

Animal Name (COURTESY) - this animal is posted as a public courtesy using information provided by the owner. Our shelter does not own or guarantee the information provided by the owner to be complete and accurate. Also, adoption does not involve our shelter but is strictly between the adopter and the owner.

LOOK AT THIS SCRAGGLY VAGABOND NOW!!! UNPOLISHED GEM!UPDATE 1/7/21 per Sigrid:
Fergus (a Pit Bull mix) is @4 years old and weighs 55 pounds. The poor little guy came to us about as scraggly a looking vagabond as you can imagine-skinny, dirty, a moth-eaten looking coat. Without complaint, he dealt with weekly medicated baths and days of isolation, until he was given a clean bill of health by our vet. Now, he has a glimmering black coat, spirit in his eyes, and a happy dog tongue. This boy has gone from hang-dog to Mr. Handsome. He never fails to be delighted to see anyone for any reason. His spirit is one of love and trust. You can tell Fergus wants nothing more than to give his devotion to anyone who will give him half a chance.
He keeps his room as clean as he is able and enjoys his bed and soft bedding. He loves chewing a doggie bone and so far has kept his chewing to his chew toys. He is smart, very strong, and lively so he will need a caretaker who can teach him good citizenship and make sure he gets plenty of exercise. Sometimes, he doesn't know his own strength so he might be too much for small children. Fergus shows interest in meeting other dogs but has not been formally introduced to any at the center yet.
To reinforce his fun-loving nature, we have learned that Fergus thinks playing Tug-O-War with a rope toy is a blast. He is careful with your hands and will politely give up the win when you want to take the toy away. Besides that, he has become an enthusiast fetch game player and will chase and bring back the rope, then gladly offer you his prize, while he gently leans against your leg and looks up at you with his wasn't-I-a-good-boy-face. How can anyone resist that!
This boy is an unpolished gem just waiting to shine. Are you the one who will see the treasure within? VOLUNTEERS and DONATIONS NEEDED. Visit our website for more info: http://nelsonspca.org

animal.description:
NAME:  Figgy
BREED:  Border Collie Mix
GENDER:  Spayed Female
AGE:  6 yrs
WEIGHT:  65 lbs
COAT:  Short
COLOR:  Tri-Color
ACTIVITY LEVEL:  Very Active Companion
LOCATION:  Fort Washington, MD

Meet Figgy!

Figgy is an affectionate, loving and sweet dog, a great companion and friend.   She is very adorable and huggable, loves baseball, when she can snuggle on the bed, loves to be touched and stroked and lives for treats, especially greenies which is her after-dinner love. She is spayed and was already obedience trained somewhat when we adopted her. We sent her for live-in reinforcement training for two months. She loves company and greets everyone energetically, then calms down immediately. A great guard dog, she informs of any approaching visitors. Fast and agile, she loves her privacy back yard and there chases squirrels, groundhogs, possums, feral cats and is a great mole digger.

Highly intelligent and easily trained, she learns new commands, directions and instructions with one or two lessons. She learned in 45 seconds how to use the dog door insert in sliding glass doors. She taught herself to stop and wait until the nose leash is on the walking side. Figgy loves to ride in the car; however, she needs a little treat to jump in. She did not like our new car, walking around and marking all the tires. For a treat in the back, she forgot the newness and jumped in. She knows when it’s time to go for her two walks a day. She yaps when she needs to go out.

Anyone who accepts Figgy will love her, and she will return that love with great enthusiasm and care. She needs younger people than 80 year olds who can run and play with her energetically.

I am 80 years old and recently widowed. Figgy is highly energetic I do not think she will be good with children since she has not been around any.  Families with teenagers should be avoided since they can be irresponsible and let her out. She needs a family on a farm or with fenced in property who can give her agility exercises, run with her and pay more attention than an 80 year old.

If you are interested in Figgy, please contact her mom, Mrs. Clemmer Montague with the email link, or call or text at 240-472-9853.

Please note that we only use PetFinder to list our courtesy dogs. Contact us through PetFinder only. We are not associated with any other listing websites.
