You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.Marshall County Humane Society is now following CDC guidelines for Covid-19 in order to keep everyone as safe as possible. We are showing dogs and cats to prospective adopters, but only on the grounds outside our shelter. We will need appointment to show the animal and we will want to have social distancing of 6' while you are there and we are wearing masks. We are doing Zoom interviews to see inside of your home since we aren't going into homes for home visit. We do come to your home before finalizing adoption to check the security of your fence if you are adopting a dog. Our dogs are given much care and attention and we treat every medical need of animal once we take them in.
MCHS is a limited intake adoption center. We are an all volunteer, non-profit organization. All of our animals are disease free, have been spayed/neutered and are up to date on shots. We charge a Dog adoption fee of $125 which includes a microchip. Our Cat adoption fee is $75.00. Most of our dogs will require a fenced yard. To fill out application, go to our website Marshallcountyhumanesociety.org, go to Adoption Info tab and click on Application. For more info, call 662-564-2900. I'm a young Labrador Retriever blend who just needs a new family to love. My estimated date of birth is early 2020. I'm pretty friendly and calm so would be a good family dog. Come and see me soon by calling 662-564-2900 or E-mail DogsNCats11@gmail.com to make an appointment to meet me.
All our animals have been spayed or neutered and up to date on all preventives and shots and we are microchipped. Dog adoption fee is $125.
Fill out application at Marshallcountyhumanesociety.org and go to Adoption Info Tab.

animal.description: Mason is approximately a 1 year old standard male aussie. He was found roaming the streets and taken to a local shelter. He came in extremely thin with overgrown nails and what appeared to be an injury to his eye. After a thorough vet check and visit to the eye specialist, Mason has a clean bill of health. While he does not have vision in his right eye, it doesn't require removal or any maintenance at this time. The vet did state that should it seem to bother him in the future, eye drops for inflammation could help. Mason is a lovely boy and still learning all the ins and outs of being a house dog. He is finally house and crate trained and thrives on routine. He does need some additional work on leash training as he hasn't mastered that yet. He also jumps up when excited so will need some redirection there but he isn't unmanageable. He would do fine in a home with children who are respectful. He also would love a home with another doggy playmate. Fenced yard required.

animal.description:
Hi there, I’m Baloo! 

I’m a 2 year old Australian Shepherd! My foster mom thinks I’m pretty cool. I hadn’t had much socialization before living with my foster mom, so I’m a little weary of people at first, but once I get to know you I’m as loyal as can be. I’ve had to learn how to fend for myself before being rescued, so that can make me a little guarded around some other dogs and my resources, but don’t let that scare you - I just need an owner who will be patient with me and give me a chance to overcome my past. I have so much love to give! I’m really in need of an owner who can give me their love, time, and attention. I’m a herding dog in need of a job. Some training would do me well! I’m already potty trained and crate trained and have so much potential! Some things I enjoy are playing tug of war, squeaky toys, and playing with my foster sister outside. I am very loving, happy, and super cuddly. When my foster mom comes home I always let out a nice big “arooo” to let her know how excited I am to see her! I hope you will take a chance on me, I’m looking for my life-long best friend!

Baloo will require a tall (6ft+) privacy fence.

animal.description: Spree is an active, smart, and playful girl. She is excellent at playing fetch and drops the toy right by you, then looks up at you until you throw the toy again. She likes to give doggy hugs and also likes getting her hips scratched. Spree is a quick learner and food-motivated, and since she's barely out of puppyhood she can learn all the tricks. Spree participates in play group almost every day and has a long list of doggy friends, but her rough-and-rowdy play style can sometimes annoy calmer dogs. She has potential to go to a home with another dog who can keep up with her.

animal.description:
Cookie is a 4 year old female pitbull mix. She’s current on age appropriate core vaccinations, is already spayed and tested negative for heartworm. Cookie is a sweet, playful, well behaved girl who has done well with the other dogs. While Cookie initially did not show a lot of interest in the cats she was briefly introduced to, we have learned Cookie is not cat friendly and will need to be in a cat free home. Cookie seems to do well in a crate. She does jump some, her foster family is working on that with her. Cookie weighs about 54 lbs.

As a reminder, to be considered for adoption, you must first submit a completed application for approval. Applications will only be accepted if all of the dogs and cats in your home are current on their core vaccinations and they are also already spayed or neutered. For more information and to download an application, please visit: www.mainelabrescue.com/adopt. If you have an approved application or have submitted an application in recent weeks, please email adopt@mainelabrescue.com to let us know of your interest in this pet.

Please do not apply for a pet that is currently available if you are going on vacation and wish to wait until you return home before adopting or if you are not able to schedule an adoption appointment on or before the coming weekend. We cannot hold pets for future adoption appointments, nor can we hold adopted pets for future pick up.

Inquiries for each available dog or cat will be considered in the order of arrival and a meet and greet will be offered to each pet’s right fit, first in line approved applicant. Please note, if you are interested in more than one pet, please list the order of your interest in your emailed inquiry. It will not be possible to meet more than one pet during an appointment.

Please note: at this time we are unable to accept applications or adopt to residents from states other than Maine, New Hampshire and Vermont.

Due to Massachusetts import laws, which are unrelated to the pandemic, we are unable to adopt to MA residents. Any questions regarding these laws should be directed to Massachusetts Department of Agriculture.

This pet is currently in a foster home here in Maine.

For more information on the adoption process, fees, and to download an application, please copy and paste this link in a browser: www.mainelabrescue.com/adopt. 

If you already have an approved application on file and are interested in this pet, please email adopt@mainelabrescue.com. Applications and inquiries from approved applicants are processed in the order received.If you have not yet submitted an application to us and are interested in adopting one of our pets, we recommend you include a completed application with your email. Please copy and past this link into your browser  for answers to our most frequently asked questions: www.mainelabrescue.com/adoption-faqs

Check out our Facebook page: www.facebook.com/MaineLabRescue

animal.description:
Hi, my name is Chloe! I'm estimated to be a Lab/Pit/Mastiff mix born around 3/16/2016.  I came up to Wisconsin from Texas and weigh 104 pounds. I'm a chunky girl and would benefit from some extra walks.  I love to say hi to people but hold on because I'll pull my way over to everyone just to say hello.  I was adopted but had to come back because I'm not good with other dogs.  I was excellent in the house though, doing great with pottying outside and I could be trusted loose while alone.  I know several commands and I'm mellow except when other animals are around.  Obedience classes for adult dogs and puppies can be incredibly helpful for both animals and humans. It helps you understand what makes me tick and will give me a better idea of what you want me to do. It’s a win/win and it will also strengthen the bond between us! Apply for me today!

My adoption fee is $60.00. Adoption applications can be filled out at CCHS or online through our website, www.cchs-petshelter.org. Applications are not first come, first served. All applications will be reviewed by the adoption committee and the home chosen will be the one considered to be the best match. All dogs and puppies have been vaccinated for Distemper and Bordetella, dewormed and microchipped. If old enough, they will be vaccinated for Rabies and blood tested for Heartworm, Lymes, Anaplasmosis and Erlichiosis. Dogs and puppies will be spayed or neutered before adoption.

CCHS is proud to be a No-Kill Humane Society. As a private, non-profit charity, our work depends on donations and volunteers to keep going. We are committed to helping the animals that enter our doors and finding each the best possible forever home. CCHS has been inspected and licensed by the Department of Animal Health - DATCP. Our license is #268235-DS

animal.description:
Lady needs a home with an existing friendly dog to show her the ropes.  She's timid and very submissive with people and other dogs.  


Lady and one other hound were dumped.  A friend called to say she saw a guy pull over the side of the road, take the dogs collars off and dumped them.  Looks like Lady has just had puppies.  Sadly as rescues we see mom dumped this time of year bc they are bred so their puppies can be sold as Christmas puppies :(  Lady is very skinny, this poor girl was just used for quick cash then discarded like trash.  She is SO sweet and kind...but shy.  You can tell she's not used to living inside the house, but absolutely loves it that she is let inside.  She gets along great with other dogs...big and small and cats.  The family who is fostering her has both dogs and cats and she's done great with everyone.  If you are interested in giving this sweet girl a forever loving home, please submit an application on our site:

www.dogworldrescue.com/adopt

We are an all volunteer rescue.  Our adoption fee of $400 is paid directly to the vet's office to help us with the dog's medical bills.

CRATE TRAINED:  Yes
LEASH TRAINED:  Yes

SPECIAL NEEDS:  No
HOME W/ SMALL CHILDREN:  Over 10 years
HOME W/ OTHER DOGS:           MALE:  Yes        FEMALE:  Yes
HOME W/ CATS:  Unknown
MICROCHIP BRAND and #:  AKC ReUnite  0006C4F4A6   
MONTHLY HEARTWORM DATE:  13th of each month
FOSTER HOME:  Chris, cbly58@icloud.com
RESCUE #:  2020-11-12-01

BIO UPDATE (1/16/21):
Max has settled into our foster home.  He is a very sweet boy. He has embraced daily walks and gets excited when he sees his leash.  He loves to cuddle and being petted and will nudge your hand for more.

Max will let you know when its meal time as that is his favorite time of the day.

He does have some medical issues that require daily medications. That will be an additional cost but he is so worth it.

He sleeps well thru the nite (currently in an open crate). Max gets along well with our female and respects her.  He seems to be fully housetrained (not one accident so far)

Max so deserves his own forever home who will love & care for him-are you that home?
BIO:  Max came from a Shelter in north Georgia. We can’t imagine why anyone would turn him in! In just a few words he’s sweet, friendly, and gets along with all dogs. He does like to beg from the table but we don’t give him people food and no one should.  It's not good for him. Our wish list for Max includes:
  - A fenced yard is a must
  - Another dog or two to pal around with
  - Someone that is home a lot to keep him company because he does love his people
  - No apartments or high-rises

After coming into rescue, Max had his gall bladder removed. He has fully recovered and is doing fine without it!  During his initial vet exam, we also found he has a 4/6 heart murmur but no clinical signs of distress.  He is on two meds to help with the blood flow.

Max loves to cuddle with either you or your dog.  He is one of the easiest fosters we've had.

Please keep in mind that not only will you have the monthly heartworm prevention but you'll also have Vetmedin and Enalapril to purchase each month.  Sadly, Max also has dry eyes so he'll need artificial tears.

Don’t let any of that scare you off... he is a dream to foster! 

============== Information for All Dogs/Adopters ==============

If you have questions about this dog, please feel free to contact the foster home at the email address listed above.  They have the most up-to-date information concerning the dog and would be happy to answer any questions about the animal. 

We welcome out of state and Canadian adoptions, but we will not ship any dog via cargo.  You will have to make arrangements to pick up the dog or for them to go by ground transport.  If you choose transporting by either volunteers through our organization or by paid transporter, there will be an additional $45 fee added for the required Health Certificate. 

We will not adopt into CT, RI, NH, ME, or MA due to strict laws regarding importation of dogs into those states.  If you have an issue with this, you need to take this up with your legislatures.

To understand the adoption process through AADR, please review the Adoption Information on our home page.  Transportation options are outlined on that page in Step 3.

If you are interested in adopting this Dachshund please review Read Before You Adopt and then you can complete an Application.

THANK YOU FOR YOUR INTEREST IN A RESCUE.

Please don't let the distance stand in your way of finding your newest best friend. We have volunteers that will help your "new friend" get up and down the East Coast and MidWest. We just can't get them from one Coast to the other but some day we hope to have enough volunteers to do that as well.  For now, please look for dogs on your coast.

animal.description:
Meet our sweet special boy Splinter!

Splinter was found on the side of the road by one of our volunteers after being hit by a car. He suffered severe back trauma which rendered him unable to use his back legs or to potty on his own.

As sad as this sounds, Splinter has not let this dim his shine one single bit ! We fitted him with a fancy wheelchair which he LOVES, he enjoys going on walks and running through the grass just like any dog. He gets around in the house with a drag bag to protect his legs from getting scuffed up and has acclimated quite well to his new normal.

Splinter loves the company of other friendly dogs, he does not enjoy small children so a home with no kids is best for this guy. Hes very shy and will bite when scared so several meets will be required in order for him to trust you enough to perform his care.
Splinter needs his bladder expressed at least every four hours, so his new family must work from home or be around enough to make sure his needs are met. He will always require this care which is quite simple once you get into a routine. He needs a home that does not have an unfenced pool, or/and access to a doggie door.

Splinter can be slow to warm up to new people but once he trusts you, you instantly become his entire world. He is crate trained but only if his doggie friends are also in their crates. 

This boy is such a sweet love, he does require maintenance, but the love you will receive in return is bigger than his special needs. Splinter is 2-3 years old and has a low to no shedding coat. 
MUST HAVE EXPERIENCE WITH SPECIAL NEEDS DOGS.

Please visit our website and fill out an application for adoption.
www.animalhelpalliance.org

For more information on Bessie please call Sierra's Haven at 1-740-353-5100. Come visit us any time to meet and get to know our pets. All dogs will be spayed/neutered, up to date on vaccines, and tested to make sure that they are heartworm negative before the adoption process can be completed. animal.description:
If you say 'happy puppy' enough, it will eventually turn into 'pappy huppy.' We're certain this must be how happy senior pup Emilio earned his nickname of pappy. (Just one look at this 12- to 13-year-old Rattie mix will convince you that it certainly can't refer to 'grand-pappy!') A strapping, handsome fellow weighing 25 lbs., Pappy Emilio has a spring in his step and the youthful enthusiasm of a dog half his age. Maybe his eyesight and hearing aren't quite what they used to be, but he'll have no trouble hearing you call him to dinner or finding his food bowl. Pappy LOVES his meals!! He also loves exploring inside the fenced acreage of his foster home with his nose to the ground, sniffing for any scents to follow. Emilio is pretty low-key and undemanding with one of the sweetest depositions you'll ever encounter. He's house-trained and lets you know when he needs to go out. He gets along with all the animals in his foster home, which includes a 12-lb. Rattie mix, a 70-lb. Rhodesian Ridgeback, three cats, and a parrot! (Occasionally he'll voice a bit of displeasure at the cats if they get too cozy with him when he's not in the mood, but that's the extent of anything even close to grumpiness.) Don't you think adopting our 'pappy huppy' Emilio would be the perfect way to close out the old year and celebrate a new one? See more photos of Emilio at https://imageevent.com/newrattitude/emiliocentralillinois .
Our adoption fee is $175 for adult dogs or $225 for puppies under 6 months old.

If you are interested in adopting this dog,
PLEASE READ THE DETAILED ADOPTION PROCESS information on our website
at www.
NewRattitude.org/adopt/

From there, you can access our adoption application or contact our Adoption Team for more info.

animal.description:
Welcome to our RMG family.... big NALA! 
Nala was surrendered to a N.Ga rescue with her lab mix brother, when the owner had surgery and couldn't care for both anymore. Another group came in to help that smaller group and took the brother but left Nala behind.This kind of stuff just breaks our hearts, because you can't explain to someone what its like to watch a dog mourn for another - until you have seen it first hand. Some other rescue friends tried to see if that rescue would take Nala as well or let them take BOTH to be reunited - but it was a no. So they already have him listed to be adopted and it appears they will never see each other again. So today when she arrived, we told her all was gonna be ok and Coal was ok too- she took a big sigh then walked away and stood at the door to come back inside. We PROMISE she is getting tons of love tonight and is curled up on the sofa! 

Since losing her brother and completing heartworm treatment, Nala has decided she would rather be an only child and soak up all of the pampering for herself. After everything she has been through, she most definitely deserves whatever she wants in life so we are looking for a home without other pets for Nala. This 70+ lb girl has plenty of love to give though so her family will not be missing out by only having one pet!

Interested in adopting this sweet, loving girl? Email adrienne@rescuemega.org or fill out an adoption application on our website- www.rmgdogs.org

He's a big lap dog and an even bigger lover! He loves giving kisses and receiving pets and head scratches! He would do best in a active home where he can exercise during the day and cuddle all night! He is house and crate trained. His favorites are car rides and watching out the window. 

His adoption fee is $150, this includes his neuter, heartworm test, vaccines current, deworming, heartworm/flea prevention and micro chipped. His dog license is also required to be purchased for Sandusky County residents at time of adoption, which is an additional $20.75.

animal.description: Want to see a huge smile on Colorado's face? Just give him a yard to run zoomies in! And if you want to see an even happier boy, give him a car ride. He loves those zoomies and especially loves those speedy car rides because he gets to be with his chauffeur person! Colorado loves his humans and wants to be with them all the time, hopefully with his head in their laps or cuddling in bed - he loves naps, too! And he loves walking with them on his leash, just pulling occasionally and easy to correct. At home, this loyal boy also loves playing tug-o-war with his people and is happy to play with his squeaky toys and rawhide bones. animal.description:
Meet Maggie!
This cutie is the first female we’ve had come through in a while. Five months ago Maggie was an unclaimed stray in an out of state shelter. She was brought up here by another area rescue and adopted by a loving home. Unfortunately, due to personal health issues and Maggie’s strength and need for leash training, the adopter has made the difficult decision to rehome Maggie. 

Maggie is estimated to be about 4 or 5 years old. She’s a strong girl with a full tail and a healthy prey drive (those dastardly squirrels are so hard to catch!). She’s a little plump right now and could stand to lose about 10 pounds (pot, meet kettle), and has a wonderful calming presence about her.

When I met her over the weekend I found a super mellow girl, with a serene, wise, queenlike temperament. As her owner says “she’s not a hugger,” and Maggie prefers not to be pet by strangers, but her reserve is not based on any fear. She’s just not into new people in general. 

She lay nearby as her owner and I chatted about her and frankly, I found her to be delightfully refreshing. She reminds me of an old fashioned Rottweiler – aloof, quiet and calm, and just not that into me. At one point she rolled onto her back for a belly rub from mom, wagging her tail beguilingly as she laid there looking at me. It was seriously adorable. Later she came up to me and solicited some attention from me. I scratched her chest and neck in the way I know my girl likes and so did Maggie. I felt privileged that this queen of a dog seemed to like me. 

Maggie loves to go for walks, playing in the yard – a game of fetch and squirrel patrol! – and chewing on bones. And tummy rubs from mom are the best. Or maybe hot dogs are the best. No, it’s belly rubs. But hot dogs are a close second. 

Maggie is a quiet, calm dog in the home, fully house trained and when left alone just snoozes on her bed until you come home. She rides in the car well and is well mannered. She generally walks well on leash but her owner says if she sees a squirrel or bunny she will pull hard, so needs some work there. Other dogs are okay on a case-by-case basis. She has an older Lab (male) she gets along well with, and a small Chihuahua too, but if another dog comes up and gets in her face suddenly she’s not okay with that and will react aggressively. In a nutshell, this is not a dog park dog.

We don’t have history with children, so no kids under 12. And with her high prey drive, no cats is probably best, since we don’t have any history there either. 

Apply to adopt Maggie here: https://spdrdogs.org/rescue-referral/how-to-adopt/ 
Washington State – Seattle area  No interstate adoptions.

animal.description:
Daisy is a sweet, beautiful, loyal and misunderstood, eight-year-old, 90-pound, female, fawn South African Boerboel Mastiff with a long tail looking for a dog-loving guardian.

Daisy was found stray in Chicago’s Avondale neighborhood in August of 2017 and was taken in by the Famous Fido shelter where she has been for over three years.

She looks like she had been bred in the past, but she is now spayed. She is nervous around new people and accepts women quicker than men. If someone would give her a chance, they will find an incredibly loyal companion. But this will take time and patience.

She doesn’t respond to commands, but she takes treats gently and appreciatively from your fingers. We think she’d do best as the one and only dog in the home, or possibly with a large male with an experienced handler.

She is healthy, spayed, vaccinated, heartworm-tested and microchipped. 

Her adoption fee of $250 benefits the Famous Fido Rescue.

To meet and possibly adopt Daisy, please fill out the application for adoption at https://famousfidorescue.org/dog-adoption-application/

And follow up on your application by e-mailing Tina at tinasells@yahoo.com to set up an appointment to meet Daisy. 

She is currently at the Famous Fido Shelter at 3124 W. Irving Park in Chicago, Illinois. After three years it’s time for Daisy to finally find her loving home.

animal.description: Maui is a 5 year old husky, chow, staffy mix according to his DNA test. He is house trained, crate trained, and has basic commands including: sit, paw, other paw, lay down, load up, and he half way knows roll over and jump up to get a treat. He needs an extremely experienced owner of either huskies or chows or both. He is crazy smart and does not respond at all to negative reinforcement. He needs positive reinforcement, consistency, and patience. Maui likes to play fetch, go swimming, and do his tricks for treats. He is not good with chickens and is not recommended for homes with children because he is very protective of his people and home and would not do well with children visitors. Maui is very vocal and is not recommended for apartment living. He does well with dogs after a proper intro and likes to play chase and wrestle. He does ok with cats as long as they don't run from him and they let him sniff them all over, however it would probably be best if he was in a home without cats. Maui needs a lot of physical and mental enrichment and does not do well if he has to be crated for long periods of time on a regular basis. He does tend to bond to one person in the house, and seems to prefer the more masculine one in the home.

animal.description:
Meet beautiful Nena but please read her complete bio before submitting an application and/or inquiring. Nena was rescued off the beach in Arroyo 
Puerto Rico with her 3 puppies who are already adopted to their forever families. Nena is being fostered with her son in Marshfield MA.
Nena is 2 years old, 40 pounds, fully vetted and microchipped.
6 days after arriving to Massachusetts, Nena was startled by a nail gun in her fosters backyard and jumped their wildlife cage and soared over the 6 foot fence. We couldn’t believe it, this had never happened before. 
Nena was missing 53 days and traveled about 75 miles through that time before being caught by Missing Dogs Massachusetts. Other than a broken toenail, she was a-ok. Due to this incident we are requesting a 6 foot fence at Nena’s new home. A visit will be required to inspect any gaps or hazards. Nena loves other dogs so will require at least one dog brother or sister. While she is more comfortable with woman she warms up to men slowly and is now walking on leash with her foster family. Nena does have a GPS collar and we will be looking for her adoptive family to provide proof of her next yearly subscription when the time comes.
Nena loves playing with other dogs, lounging in bed with constant belly rubs from foster mom and ripping her stuffed animals apart. Nena will be nervous for the first few days but is a wonderful sweet dog that will provide years of love and happiness.
Our adoption application can be found on our website on the available dogs page.
Thank you!

animal.description:
Zeus came to us as a stray that was never claimed. He is around 75 pounds and has a lot of power behind him, and he has lots of energy. We believe Zeus was born in July of 2018 and will need an experienced dog owner. He is a very happy go lucky and playful guy, but he can be a bit selective about people from time to time. He also will need to work on resource guarding as he can get defensive about having toys, or treats taken from him. He would do best as the only animal in the home with adults only. 

All pets adopted from the Humane Society of Freeborn County will have age appropriate vaccinations, testing, alterations and micro chips included in their adoption fee! Fill out an app at www.freeborncountyhs.org. 

We do allow home trials with our dogs or cats to approved applicants. This is how we make sure your new family member is the perfect fit. We ask that you allow at least a month for your new pet to adjust to their new home. They will need that time to decompress. During this time we will provide counseling to ensure a successful transition.

Please review the basic adoption requirements listed on our site before applying. We take finding the right homes for our critters very seriously as they deserve nothing but the best! Please allow a week for applications to be processed.
If listed as (Currently in Foster) - these pets are not at our facility but are in foster care homes. They are available for adoption. Meet and greets are available with approved applicants only. 

If you have any questions feel free to send us an email at freeborncohumanesociety@gmail.com. Don't forget to check us out on Facebook!

animal.description:
Maple is a precious puppy who is a part of a litter of 5 that were all saved from a local kill shelter. Their estimated date of birth is 8/13/20. At 3.5 months old, Maple currently weighs 25 pounds and has a gorgeous, shiny black coat with a bit of white on her nose, chin, chest and belly. Friendly & sweet, Maple loves everyone she meets. She is used to being crated at night and playing in a safe, fenced yard during the day with other dogs. Maple is fine with the other pups here and should be fine with cats and other animals if introduced as a puppy. Maple is crate trained, sleeps on a big orthopedic bed and has lots of toys and a fluffy bed in her crate that she does not chew. She is now fully vetted and ready for her forever home. Maple's wish list consists of an inside forever home with a big fenced yard for playtime, a home with lots of toys and another doggy friend for play time and pet parents who understand the time commitment that a puppy requires. Adopters who are retired or work-from-home parents are ideal as they have the time to spend with the pet. Adopters committed to doing a 6 week basic obedience class to ensure Maple's continued success at being a good canine citizen would also a plus. If you think you have the perfect home for Maple, contact us at info.caresga@gmail.com for an adoption application. We adopt up north and all over so please ask for details. $400 adoption fee and a vet reference is required to ensure a great home (this means you have had a pet so we can call to verify their level of care). Eligibility for adoption means your current or past pets are spayed/neutered, up to date on vaccines and on monthly heartworm and flea prevention. Please be aware that we do not allow shock collars (ie underground fences) or "pens" as an alternative for a fenced yard.

We do our best to place our rescue pets in the very best homes. Please be aware that we have an application which also includes required vet records showing your existing pets are current on preventative medical care. Puppy adopters please take note that we generally try to place our puppies into homes where at least one parent is retired/stay at home/works from home to ensure the puppy gets enough attention and training (puppies cannot hold it all day in a crate) so please have a plan ready when contacting us. For safety reasons, we try not to place small dogs or puppies in families with children under 5 (there may be exceptions depending on situation).

Typical adoption fees for puppies are $350, juvenile dogs $300, adults dogs are $250, senior dogs are $150. Some pets, smaller dogs for example, may have a higher than normal adoption fee but we will alert you if there is a variance. Dogs rescued from China always have a higher adoption fee. Adoption fees help our group offset PART of the cost of rescuing, rehabilitating, and getting the pet healthy so they can go on to find a loving home with someone willing to give them a second chance at life. This amount includes each animal being current on age appropriate vaccinations including DHPPL, bordetella, influenza, rabies, and boosters when appropriate. De-wormed for any internal parasites (round worms, hook worms, tape worms and whipworms) with Drontal Plus, 4DX tested heart-worm negative (if positive, they are treated), tested negative for tick borne diseases, spayed/neutered, implanted with a micro-chip and have been examined by a veterinarian to certify that they are healthy. Any other known health issues are treated as well prior to adoption (examples: UTI, broken bones, contagious infections, dental cleanings, etc). All animals are also on a regime of flea and heartworm medication every month. Lifetime registration for the micro-chip is included in each adoption fee. In addition, each adopter will go home with a fitted collar, tags, a bag of dog food the pet has been on, copies of all vet history, and an adoption kit filled with valuable information and coupons as well as other various treats or toys as promotions become available. All puppy adoptions include two puppy training books, the Puppy Primer & Way To Go by Patricia McConnell, and all adult adoptions go home with Love Has No Age Limit by Patricia McConnell to help ensure a smooth transition for your new family member.

We ask that you consider an additional donation on top of this pet's adoption fee. This money will go directly into our Adoption Fund to be used exclusively for rescuing and caring for other pets in need. Many pets we take in have very high vet bills to get them healthy and adoptable for the public - much higher than their adoption fees. We receive no government funding and rely solely on donations from our community and caring adopters to continue our rescue efforts!

animal.description:
Caroline came to us as part of a litter of 6 week old puppies from a kill shelter. We held her back from being adopted because she was showing some rear lameness issues. After several exams including radiographs it was determined that it was probably panosteitis which is self limited (growing pains that goes away on its own). Caroline is currently 48 pounds at 11 months old (DOB 11/13/19) which is probably her adult weight (she could actually stand to lose a few pounds). She has a gorgeous black & tan coat, walks well on a leash and is crate trained, In addition she does very well in the house - she is house trained and doesn't chew. Caroline is playful, adores toys and enjoys playing in a fenced yard. Caroline is a sweet girl and loves attention. Caroline can be particular about dogs when first meeting them but is okay with several of our dogs here. However she was adopted once and returned for "growling" at their other dog (we feel she wasn't given enough time to acclimate before returning) so she may be better suited as an only dog or in a home with an older bigger dog that she likes. Caroline is treat motivated and already knows sit & down. She is a precious pup who deserves the very best home. Caroline's wish list consists of an inside forever home with a big fenced yard for playtime, a home with lots of toys and pet parents who understand the time commitment that a dog requires. Adopters who are retired or work-from-home parents are ideal as they have the time to spend with the pet. We do our best to place our rescue pets in the very best homes. Please be aware that we have an application which also includes required vet records showing your existing pets are current on preventative medical care. Puppy adopters please take note that we generally try to place our puppies into homes where at least one parent is retired/stay at home/works from home to ensure the puppy gets enough attention and training (puppies cannot hold it all day in a crate) so please have a plan ready when contacting us. For safety reasons, we try not to place small dogs or puppies in families with children under 5 (there may be exceptions depending on situation).

Typical adoption fees for puppies are $350, juvenile dogs $300, adults dogs are $250, senior dogs are $150. Some pets, smaller dogs for example, may have a higher than normal adoption fee but we will alert you if there is a variance. Dogs rescued from China always have a higher adoption fee. Adoption fees help our group offset PART of the cost of rescuing, rehabilitating, and getting the pet healthy so they can go on to find a loving home with someone willing to give them a second chance at life. This amount includes each animal being current on age appropriate vaccinations including DHPPL, bordetella, influenza, rabies, and boosters when appropriate. De-wormed for any internal parasites (round worms, hook worms, tape worms and whipworms) with Drontal Plus, 4DX tested heart-worm negative (if positive, they are treated), tested negative for tick borne diseases, spayed/neutered, implanted with a micro-chip and have been examined by a veterinarian to certify that they are healthy. Any other known health issues are treated as well prior to adoption (examples: UTI, broken bones, contagious infections, dental cleanings, etc). All animals are also on a regime of flea and heartworm medication every month. Lifetime registration for the micro-chip is included in each adoption fee. In addition, each adopter will go home with a fitted collar, tags, a bag of dog food the pet has been on, copies of all vet history, and an adoption kit filled with valuable information and coupons as well as other various treats or toys as promotions become available. All puppy adoptions include two puppy training books, the Puppy Primer & Way To Go by Patricia McConnell, and all adult adoptions go home with Love Has No Age Limit by Patricia McConnell to help ensure a smooth transition for your new family member.

We ask that you consider an additional donation on top of this pet's adoption fee. This money will go directly into our Adoption Fund to be used exclusively for rescuing and caring for other pets in need. Many pets we take in have very high vet bills to get them healthy and adoptable for the public - much higher than their adoption fees. We receive no government funding and rely solely on donations from our community and caring adopters to continue our rescue efforts!

animal.description:
Hello. I'm Chico! Hi there, I'm Diamond! Together, we are a wonderful set of Chihuahua Chums. We've always been together and we'll be staying together in our adoptive home. Yep, that's right, we're a package deal. Lucky for you, we are a cute, sweet, friendly bonded pair of little Lap Dogs so if you're the "more the merrier" type, consider making us part of your family.  

We are tiny, about four pounds each -- soaking wet -- which, to be honest, we don't really like to be. Are there chihuahuas out there that like to be soaking wet? Probably not. That's more of a Labrador trait, don't you think? But we digress. 

Here's another stat about us. At this point in our lives we've been told we are seniors *eye roll* because we are now around 7-8 years of age. However, please be advised that we are full of life and are very happy, snuggly, adorable boys, so age is really irrelevant we think. Who else doesn't love naps? Show of hands. We certainly like our siestas, and to be held and cuddled and doted on, but we also like exploring the yard, causing a little mischief here or there, and getting fresh air. 

We're a great pair of dogs that are looking for a great home that will love us for the rest of our days. Which aren't numbered, as the label "senior" suggests. We've got lots of years left in us, so take a chance and come meet us to see if we choose you! Love, Chico and Diamond

animal.description:
Ram is sweet and adorable and looking for a great forever home!

Ram's owner could no longer care for him, so he came to our rescue. He loves to cuddle with a person, and is affectionate. Ram is on two different seizures medications (Keppa and Phenobarbital) which he gets 3x/day and so he needs someone home most of the time. He will need regular bloodwork at the vets. Additionally, he is not housebroken, and we are not sure if this is a neurological issue. He is also mostly deaf. His seizure medicine is expensive and he needs regular bloodwork to ensure his phenobarbital level is at the correct therapeutic dose. 

He recently was groomed, and he will need to be groomed and brushed on a regular basis. He is very sweet, but timid at first, and would do best in a home with no kids or older kids. He just got a dental and had 2 teeth extracted and a small mass removed from his mouth which was sent out to be biopsied. 

We require an adoption application, phone interview, virtual house check, and meet and greet with your entire family. Send us an email at petprofilerescue@gmail.com for a for an adoption application or apply online at: https://docs.google.com/forms/d/1S5v9x1oGSYLBSfheZJ_zSvkIHoT3Fe_xnsq5V75IX9w/edit?fbclid=IwAR0rU1zQezgZhhC_01_JpMFhujOq40cu8Xl4xKdiZ0b1L-3Pwm1Et-XI3K4
If you have already submitted an application to us, send us an email, expressing your interest in this dog. We are foster based in the Chicago area.

Please consider SPONSORING Ram to help with his medical needs. You can click on the "Sponsor" button or Donations can be made to our Paypal at petprofilerescue@gmail.com or https://paypal.me/petprofilerescue to help with Ram's medical care. 

Our rescue dogs' Amazon Wishlist is here: https://www.amazon.com/hz/wishlist/ls/1PIG0Y2YAZ2MP…

Sully is a young male who was previously fostered with another larger dog. He has been spending time with our trainer to help him build confidence in real-life situations (and has been making great improvements). He is inherently a skittish dog, that is very uncertain of new people. He will do best with a confident and assertive owner who understands the necessary and proper leadership vital to his success. He is so loyal and sweet. To continue to do well, he will need someone to hold him accountable and work him through his fears. Sully would do best in a quiet household . No kids.

----
For more information email mitliebegsdr@gmail.com or fill out an application on our website www.mlgsdr.com

Mika is a 2 year old female German Shepherd looking for a home who can manage her over-protective nature. Mika has been through professional training and is working on approriate behaviors when meeting new people, especially men. Her mistrust and behavior is manageable with a strong leader and consistency. She is not a good candidate for a home with children.

Mika gets along well with other dogs and is very playful. She would do well in a home with another younger playful confident dog as she tends to be more friendly around visitors when the other dogs are getting attention. As time goes on she is less anxious around unknown people when there are other dogs being friendly. They have been helping her be a better dog.

She is a wonderful hiking partner and stays close and has very good recall. She knows all her basic commands and is house trained. She is an extremely intelligent dog who would benefit from being mentally challenged like nose work or something.

It will most likely take several meetings with Mika before she is comfortable with her new adoptive home. We will require a patient adopter that is committed to continuing her training and helping her succeed in uncertain situations.

IMPORTANT!!!   All adoptions are by appointment only going forward and are spaced 30 minutes apart. PLEASE call the shelter directly during business hours for more information (see number below).  You need to make sure that the animal in which you have an interest is still available and to set up an appointment to meet the specific animal.  Once you arrive at the shelter for your scheduled appointment, please follow the directions that you were given over the telephone. If you are running late for your appointment or will be unable to make your scheduled appointment time, notify staff immediately. This will enable them to schedule that time for another prospective adoptive family. If necessary, they will be able to reschedule your appointment to a more convenient time.  

BLUE is the other half of a pair of dogs surrendered to the shelter on 12/7. The two male dogs are bird dogs/hounds and are estimated to be six years of age. Neither one had been neutered prior to arrival. Because they are new to the shelter, staff does not yet have hands on experience with the two dogs and cannot provide information about their temperament, personalities, likes or dislikes. However, what information they do have they will share with you if you give them a call or when you go there for an adoption appointment. You can meet either one or both dogs in person. However, because neither one has been neutered, that will need to be done before you could take either one home with you. Please read the important information below. 

Adoption fees are $80 for dogs.  Cat adoption fees are $50. Cash or check only. 
NOTE: All shelter fees are under review and may be changed or modified at any time without advance notice.

The shelter routinely vaccinates all healthy appearing animals upon their arrival at the shelter and deworms them.  Any animals not already spayed/neutered must have the procedure done through the veterinary clinic that contracts with the county before that animal can be released from the clinic to the new family. By state law, animals old enough to be given a rabies vaccine, must have that vaccine done, as well.  The vaccine is given by the veterinary clinic staff at a separate cost to the adoptive family. 

Hold periods for every incoming animal vary for several reasons including, but not limited to, whether the animal came in from the Cumberland County area, or from the City of Crossville, which contracts with the county for its animal shelter services.  Check with the staff to verify the availability date of every animal for which you have an interest.

For more information on this pet, call the shelter at (931)484-8525. The shelter is open Monday, Tuesday, Thursday, Friday, and Saturday from 10am to 2pm. Closed Wednesday and Sunday and county observed holidays.

animal.description:
Hello there, my name is Indy but you may remember me as Zach, when I was posted a few months ago.  Unfortunately, my previous adoption did not work out as I am a rowdy player and the current dog in the home was much more timid.  I have fun playing with the coonhound in my foster home and I am looking for a spot where people understand I am still very much a young pup.  I like to play and be busy, and without constructive activity, I can find naughty things to do, like chew on non-dog toys.  On the positive, I am fully house trained and even use a bell to indicate I want out.  (How smart is that?!?) Mom says I am so loving, and I especially love romping around outdoors with foster dad.  Because I am so young and active, mom does not want me to go to a home where I am alone all day, so I need a family that is gone for shorter periods.  I go in my crate easily but don't want to be there all day.  I also need a fenced yard.  I am a good boy, and will really shine in the right environment.  

If interested in me, please fill out the adoption application under the "Adoption" heading on our website www.bassetbuddiesrescue.org and a volunteer will reach out to you.
